# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: differential-geometry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] In geometry, the notion of a **connection** makes precise the idea of transporting local geometric objects, such as tangent vectors or tensors in the tangent space, along a curve or family of curves in a *parallel* and consistent manner.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] There are various kinds of connections in modern geometry, depending on what sort of data one wants to transport.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] For instance, an affine connection, the most elementary type of connection, gives a means for parallel transport of tangent vectors on a manifold from one point to another along a curve.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] An affine connection is typically given in the form of a covariant derivative, which gives a means for taking directional derivatives of vector fields, measuring the deviation of a vector field from being parallel in a given direction.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] Connections are of central importance in modern geometry in large part because they allow a comparison between the local geometry at one point and the local geometry at another point.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] Differential geometry embraces several variations on the connection theme, which fall into two major groups: the infinitesimal and the local theory.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] The local theory concerns itself primarily with notions of parallel transport and holonomy.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] The infinitesimal theory concerns itself with the differentiation of geometric data.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] Thus a covariant derivative is a way of specifying a derivative of a vector field along another vector field on a manifold.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] A Cartan connection is a way of formulating some aspects of connection theory using differential forms and Lie groups.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] An Ehresmann connection is a connection in a fibre bundle or a principal bundle by specifying the allowed directions of motion of the field.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] A Koszul connection is a connection which defines directional derivative for sections of a vector bundle more general than the tangent bundle.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] Connections also lead to convenient formulations of *geometric invariants*, such as the curvature (see also curvature tensor and curvature form), and torsion tensor.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] Suppose that a tangent vector to the sphere *S* is given at the north pole, and we are to define a manner of consistently moving this vector to other points of the sphere: a means for *parallel transport*.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] Naively, this could be done using a particular coordinate system.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] However, unless proper care is applied, the parallel transport defined in one system of coordinates will not agree with that of another coordinate system.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] A more appropriate parallel transportation system exploits the symmetry of the sphere under rotation.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] Given a vector at the north pole, one can transport this vector along a curve by rotating the sphere in such a way that the north pole moves along the curve without axial rolling.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] This latter means of parallel transport is the Levi-Civita connection on the sphere.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] If two different curves are given with the same initial and terminal point, and a vector *v* is rigidly moved along the first curve by a rotation, the resulting vector at the terminal point will be *different from* the vector resulting from rigidly moving *v* along the second curve.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] This phenomenon reflects the curvature of the sphere.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] A simple mechanical device that can be used to visualize parallel transport is the south-pointing chariot.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] For instance, suppose that *S* is a sphere given coordinates by the stereographic projection.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] Regard *S* as consisting of unit vectors in **R**3.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] Then *S* carries a pair of coordinate patches corresponding to the projections from north pole and south pole.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] cover a neighborhood *U*0 of the north pole and *U*1 of the south pole, respectively.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] Let *X*, *Y*, *Z* be the ambient coordinates in **R**3.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] Let us now represent a vector field v on S (an assignment of a tangent vector to each point in S) in local coordinates.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] We come now to the main question of defining how to transport a vector field parallelly along a curve.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] Suppose that *P*(*t*) is a curve in *S*.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] Naïvely, one may consider a vector field parallel if the coordinate components of the vector field are constant along the curve.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] However, an immediate ambiguity arises: in *which* coordinate system should these components be constant?
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] For instance, suppose that *v*(*P*(*t*)) has constant components in the *U*1 coordinate system.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] But $\left({\frac {d}{dt}}J_{\varphi _{01}}\left(\varphi _{1}^{-1}(P(t))\right)\right)$ is always a non-singular matrix (provided that the curve *P*(*t*) is not stationary), so **v**1 and **v**0 *cannot ever be* simultaneously constant along the curve.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] The problem observed above is that the usual directional derivative of vector calculus does not behave well under changes in the coordinate system when applied to the components of vector fields.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] This makes it quite difficult to describe how to translate vector fields in a parallel manner, if indeed such a notion makes any sense at all.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] There are two fundamentally different ways of resolving this problem.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] The first approach is to examine what is required for a generalization of the directional derivative to "behave well" under coordinate transitions.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] This is the tactic taken by the covariant derivative approach to connections: good behavior is equated with covariance.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] Here one considers a modification of the directional derivative by a certain linear operator, whose components are called the Christoffel symbols, which involves no derivatives on the vector field itself.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] where Γ depends on the coordinate system *φ* and is bilinear in **u** and **v**.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] In particular, Γ does not involve any derivatives on **u** or **v**.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] In this approach, Γ must transform in a prescribed manner when the coordinate system *φ* is changed to a different coordinate system.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] This transformation is not tensorial, since it involves not only the *first derivative* of the coordinate transition, but also its *second derivative*.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] Specifying the transformation law of Γ is not sufficient to determine Γ uniquely.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] Some other normalization conditions must be imposed, usually depending on the type of geometry under consideration.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] In Riemannian geometry, the Levi-Civita connection requires compatibility of the Christoffel symbols with the metric (as well as a certain symmetry condition).
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] With these normalizations, the connection is uniquely defined.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] The second approach is to use Lie groups to attempt to capture some vestige of symmetry on the space.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] This is the approach of Cartan connections.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] The example above using rotations to specify the parallel transport of vectors on the sphere is very much in this vein.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] Historically, connections were studied from an infinitesimal perspective in Riemannian geometry.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] The infinitesimal study of connections began to some extent with Elwin Christoffel.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] This was later taken up more thoroughly by Gregorio Ricci-Curbastro and Tullio Levi-Civita (Levi-Civita & Ricci 1900) who observed in part that a connection in the infinitesimal sense of Christoffel also allowed for a notion of parallel transport.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] The work of Levi-Civita focused exclusively on regarding connections as a kind of differential operator whose parallel displacements were then the solutions of differential equations.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] As the twentieth century progressed, Élie Cartan developed a new notion of connection.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] He sought to apply the techniques of Pfaffian systems to the geometries of Felix Klein's Erlangen program.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] In these investigations, he found that a certain infinitesimal notion of connection (a Cartan connection) could be applied to these geometries and more: his connection concept allowed for the presence of curvature which would otherwise be absent in a classical Klein geometry.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] (See, for example, (Cartan 1926) and (Cartan 1983).) Furthermore, using the dynamics of Gaston Darboux, Cartan was able to generalize the notion of parallel transport for his class of infinitesimal connections.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] This established another major thread in the theory of connections: that a connection is a certain kind of differential form.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] The two threads in connection theory have persisted through the present day: a connection as a differential operator, and a connection as a differential form.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] In 1950, Jean-Louis Koszul (Koszul 1950) gave an algebraic framework for regarding a connection as a differential operator by means of the Koszul connection.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] The Koszul connection was both more general than that of Levi-Civita, and was easier to work with because it finally was able to eliminate (or at least to hide) the awkward Christoffel symbols from the connection formalism.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] The attendant parallel displacement operations also had natural algebraic interpretations in terms of the connection.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] Koszul's definition was subsequently adopted by most of the differential geometry community, since it effectively converted the *analytic* correspondence between covariant differentiation and parallel translation to an *algebraic* one.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] In that same year, Charles Ehresmann (Ehresmann 1950), a student of Cartan's, presented a variation on the connection as a differential form view in the context of principal bundles and, more generally, fibre bundles.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] Ehresmann connections were, strictly speaking, not a generalization of Cartan connections.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] Cartan connections were quite rigidly tied to the underlying differential topology of the manifold because of their relationship with Cartan's equivalence method.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] Ehresmann connections were rather a solid framework for viewing the foundational work of other geometers of the time, such as Shiing-Shen Chern, who had already begun moving away from Cartan connections to study what might be called gauge connections.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] In Ehresmann's point of view, a connection in a principal bundle consists of a specification of *horizontal* and *vertical* vector fields on the total space of the bundle.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] A parallel translation is then a lifting of a curve from the base to a curve in the principal bundle which is horizontal.
[src:differential-geometry/connection-mathematics] This viewpoint has proven especially valuable in the study of holonomy.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] In mathematics, **curvature** is any of several strongly related concepts in geometry that intuitively measure the amount by which a curve deviates from being a straight line or by which a surface deviates from being a plane.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] If a curve or surface is contained in a larger space, curvature can be defined *extrinsically* relative to the ambient space.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Curvature of Riemannian manifolds of dimension at least two can be defined *intrinsically* without reference to a larger space.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] For curves, curvature describes how sharply the curve bends.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] The canonical examples are circles: smaller circles bend more sharply and hence have higher curvature.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] For a point on a general curve, the direction of the curve is described by its tangent line.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] How sharply the curve is bending at that point can be measured by how much that tangent line changes direction per unit distance along the curve.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Curvature measures the angular rate of change of the direction of the tangent line, or the unit tangent vector, of the curve per unit distance along the curve.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Curvature is expressed in units of radians per unit distance.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] For a circle, that rate of change is the same at all points on the circle and is equal to the reciprocal of the circle's radius.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Straight lines don't change direction and have zero curvature.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] The curvature at a point on a twice differentiable curve is the magnitude of its curvature vector at that point and is also the curvature of its osculating circle, which is the circle that best approximates the curve near that point.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] For surfaces (and, more generally for higher-dimensional manifolds), that are embedded in a Euclidean space, the concept of curvature is more complex, as it depends on the choice of a direction on the surface or manifold.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] This leads to the concepts of *maximal curvature*, *minimal curvature*, and *mean curvature*.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] The history of curvature began with the ancient Greeks' basic distinction between straight and circular lines, with the concept later developed by figures like Aristotle and Apollonius.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] The development of calculus in the 17th century, particularly by Newton and Leibniz, provided tools to systematically calculate curvature for curves.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Euler then extended the study to surfaces, followed by Gauss's crucial insight of "intrinsic" curvature, which is independent of how a surface is embedded in space, and Riemann's generalization to higher dimensions.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] The curvature of a differentiable curve was originally defined through osculating circles.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] In this setting, Augustin-Louis Cauchy showed that the center of curvature is the intersection point of two infinitely close normal lines to the curve.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Intuitively, curvature describes for any part of a curve how much the curve direction changes over a small distance along the curve.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] The direction of the curve at any point **P** is described by a unit tangent vector, **T**.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] A section of a curve is also called an arc, and length along the curve is arc length, s.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] So the curvature for a small section of the curve is the angle of the change of the direction of the tangent vector divided by the arc length Δs.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] For a general curve which might have a varying curvature along its length, the curvature at a point **P** on the curve is the limit of the curvature of sections containing **P** as the length of the sections approaches zero.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] For a twice differentiable curve, that limit is the magnitude of the derivative of the unit tangent vector with respect to arc length.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Curvature is a differential-geometric property of the curve; it does not depend on the parametrization of the curve.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] In particular, it does not depend on the orientation of the parametrized curve, i.e. which direction along the curve is associated with increasing parameter values.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] A curve that is parametrized by arc length is a vector-valued function that is denoted by the Greek letter gamma with an overbar, –***γ***, that describes the position of a point on the curve, P, in terms of its arc-length distance, s along the curve from some other reference point on the curve.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] The parameter s can also be interpreted as a time parameter.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Then –***γ***(s) describes the path of a particle that moves along the curve at a constant unit speed.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Curvature can then be understood as a measure of how fast the direction of the particle rotates.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] A twice differentiable curve, ***γ***: [*a*, *b*] → $\mathbb {R}$ *n*, that is not parametrized by arc length can be re-parametrized by arc length provided that ***γ***′(t) is everywhere not zero, so that 1/‖***γ***′(t)‖ is always a finite positive number.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Both ***γ*** and –***γ*** trace the same path in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ and so have the same curvature vector and curvature at each point **P** on the curve.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] This is also reflected in the second expression for the curvature: the expression inside the parentheses is cos *θ*, where θ is the angle between the vectors **T** and ***γ***′′(*t*), so that the square root produces sin *θ*.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] If **γ** is twice continuously differentiable, then so is s(t) and –**γ**, while ***T***(*t*) is continuously differentiable, and ***K***(*t*) and *κ*(*t*) are continuous.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Often it is difficult or impossible to express the arc-length parametrization, –***γ***, in closed form even when **γ** is given in closed form.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] This is typically the case when it is difficult or impossible to express *s*(*t*) or its inverse *t*(*s*) in closed form.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] However curvature can be expressed only in terms of the first and second derivatives of **γ**, without direct reference to –***γ***.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] The curvature vector represents both the direction towards which the curve is turning as well as how sharply it turns.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Historically, the curvature of a differentiable curve was defined through the osculating circle, which is the circle that best approximates the curve at a point.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] More precisely, given a point **P** on a curve, every other point **Q** of the curve defines a circle (or sometimes a line) passing through **Q** and tangent to the curve at **P**.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] The osculating circle is the limit, if it exists, of this circle when **Q** tends to **P**.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Then the *center of curvature* and the *radius of curvature* of the curve at **P** are the center and the radius of the osculating circle.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] When the curvature is zero, for example on a straight line or at a point of inflection, the radius of curvature is infinite and the center of curvature is indeterminate or "at infinity".
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Given two points **P** and **Q** on a curve **γ**, let *s*(**P**,**Q**) be the arc length of the portion of the curve between **P** and **Q** and let *d*(**P**,**Q**) denote the length of the line segment from **P** to **Q**.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] where the limit is taken as the point **Q** approaches **P** on **γ**.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] The denominator can equally well be taken to be *d*(***P***,***Q***)3.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] The formula follows by verifying it for the osculating circle.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] There may be some situations where the preconditions for the above formulas do not apply, but where it is still appropriate to apply the concept of curvature.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] It can be useful to apply the concept of curvature to a curve **γ** at a point ***P*** = ***γ***(*t0*) if the one-sided derivatives for ***γ***′(*t0*) exist but are different values, or likewise for ***γ***′′(*t0*).
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] In such a case, it could be useful to describe the curve with curvature at each side.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Such might be the case of a curve that is constructed piecewise.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Another situation occurs when the limit of a ratio results in an indeterminate 0 / 0 value for the curvature, for example when both derivatives exist but are both zero.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] In such a case, it might be possible to evaluate the underlying limit using l'Hôpital's rule.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] The following are examples of curves with application of the relevant concepts and formulas.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] A geometric explanation for why the curvature of a circle of radius *R* at any point **P** is 1/*R* is partially illustrated by the diagram to the right.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] The length of the red arc is L and the measure in radians of the arc's central angle, angle ACB, is *L*/*R*.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] The angle between the arc endpoint tangents is angle BDE, which is the same size as the central angle, because both angles are supplementary to angle BDA.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] The ratio of the angle between the arc endpoint tangents, measured in radians, divided by the arc length L is (*L*/*R*)/*L* = 1/*R*.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Since the ratio is 1/*R* for any arc of the circle that is less than a half circle, for arcs containing any given point **P** on the circle, the limit of the ratio as arc length approaches zero is also 1/*R*.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Hence the curvature of the circle at any point **P** is 1/*R*.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] A common parametrization of a circle of radius r is ***γ***(*t*) = (*r* cos *t*, *r* sin *t*).
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] It follows, as expected, that the radius of curvature is the radius of the circle, and that the center of curvature is the center of the circle.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] The same circle can also be defined by the implicit equation *F*(*x*, *y*) = 0 with *F*(*x*, *y*) = *x*2 + *y*2 – *r*2.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Consider the parabola *y* = *ax*2 + *bx* + *c*.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] It is the graph of a function, with derivative 2*ax* + *b*, and second derivative 2*a*.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] This means that, if *a* > 0, the concavity is upward directed everywhere; if *a* < 0, the concavity is downward directed; for *a* = 0, the curvature is zero everywhere, confirming that the parabola degenerates into a line in this case.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] The (unsigned) curvature is maximal for *x* = –⁠*b*/2*a*⁠, that is at the stationary point (zero derivative) of the function, which is the vertex of the parabola.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] The first derivative of x is 1, and the second derivative is zero.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Substituting into the formula for general parametrizations gives exactly the same result as above, with x replaced by t and with primes referring to derivatives with respect to the parameter t.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] The same parabola can also be defined by the implicit equation *F*(*x*, *y*) = 0 with *F*(*x*, *y*) = *ax*2 + *bx* + *c* – *y*.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] As *Fy* = –1, and *Fyy* = *Fxy* = 0, one obtains exactly the same value for the (unsigned) curvature.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] However, the signed curvature is not defined for an implicit equation since the signed curvature depends on an orientation of the curve that is not provided by the implicit equation.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Let ***γ***(*t*) = (*x*(*t*), *y*(*t*)) be a proper parametric representation of a twice differentiable plane curve.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Here *proper* means that on the domain of definition of the parametrization, the derivative ⁠d***γ***/d*t*⁠ exists and is nowhere equal to the zero vector.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] where primes refer to derivatives with respect to t.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] where the numerator is the absolute value of the determinant of the 2-by-2 matrix with **γ**′ and **γ**′′ as the columns.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] These formulas can be understood as an application of the cross product formula for curvature in three dimensions.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Since the operands have zeros in the third dimension, the cross product result will have zero values for the first two dimensions, so only the value in the third dimension is relevant to calculating the magnitude of the cross product.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] The formula for the value of the third dimension thus appears in the numerator of the above formulas.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] For plane curves, it can be useful to express the curvature as a single scalar that can be positive or negative, called the **signed curvature** or **oriented curvature** and denoted with a lowercase k.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Whether k is positive or negative depends on the orientation of the curve.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Whether a positive k corresponds to clockwise or counterclockwise turning depends on the orientation of the curve and the orientation of the coordinate axes.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] With a standard orientation of the coordinate axes, when moving along the curve in the direction of increasing t, k is positive if the curve turns to the left, counterclockwise, and it is negative if the curve turns to the right, clockwise.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] This is consistent with the convention of treating counterclockwise rotations as rotations through a positive angle.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] However, since the sign of k is dependent on the orientation of the parametrization, k is not differential-geometric property property of the curve.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Except for orientation issues, the signed curvature for a plane curve captures similar information as the curvature vector, which for a plane curve is constrained to just one dimension, the line that is perpendicular to the unit tangent vector.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Using a standard orientation of the coordinate axes, let —**N** be the unit normal vector obtained from the unit tangent vector, **T**, by a counterclockwise rotation of ⁠π/2⁠.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Then —**N** is dependent on the orientation of the curve and points to the left when moving along the curve in the direction of increasing *t*.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] In the general case of a curve, the sign of the signed curvature is somewhat arbitrary, as it depends on the orientation of the curve.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] In the case of the graph of a function, there is a natural orientation by increasing values of x.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] This gives additional significance to the sign of the signed curvature.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] The sign of the signed curvature is the same as the sign of the second derivative of f.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] If it is positive then the graph has an upward concavity, and, if it is negative the graph has a downward concavity.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] If it is zero, then one has an inflection point or an undulation point.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] When the slope of the graph (that is the derivative of the function) is small, the signed curvature is well approximated by the second derivative.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] It is common in physics and engineering to approximate the curvature with the second derivative, for example, in beam theory or for deriving the wave equation of a string under tension, and other applications where small slopes are involved.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] This often allows systems that are otherwise nonlinear to be treated approximately as linear.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] The signed curvature is not defined, as it depends on an orientation of the curve that is not provided by the implicit equation.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Note that changing F into –*F* would not change the curve defined by *F*(*x*, *y*) = 0, but it would change the sign of the numerator if the absolute value were omitted in the preceding formula.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] A point of the curve where *Fx* = *Fy* = 0 is a singular point, which means that the curve is not differentiable at this point, and thus that the curvature is not defined (most often, the point is either a crossing point or a cusp).
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] A *curvature comb* can be used to represent graphically the curvature of every point on a curve.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Curvature combs are useful when combining two different curves in CAD environments.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] They provide a visual representation of the continuity between the curves.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] The continuity can be defined as being in one of four levels.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] G0 : The 2 curvature combs are at an angle at the junction.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] G1 : The teeth of the 2 combs are parallel at the junction but are of different length.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] G2 : The teeth are parallel and of the same length.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] However the tangents of the 2 combs are not the same.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] G3 : The teeth are parallel and of the same length and the tangents of the 2 combs are the same.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] The above image shows a G2 continuity at the 2 junctions.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] For a general parametrization by a parameter t, one needs expressions involving derivatives with respect to t.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] where the prime denotes differentiation with respect to the parameter t.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] These formulas are related to the general formulas for curvature and the curvature vector, except that they use the vector cross product instead of the scalar dot product to express the perpendicular component of ***γ***′′ / ‖***γ***′‖^2 relative to ***γ***′.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] The curvature of curves drawn on a surface is the main tool for the defining and studying the curvature of the surface.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Any non-singular curve on a smooth surface has its tangent vector **T** contained in the tangent plane of the surface.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Let the curve be arc-length parametrized, and let **t** = **u** × **T** so that **T**, **t**, **u** form an orthonormal basis, called the **Darboux frame**.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] All curves on the surface with the same tangent vector at a given point will have the same normal curvature, which is the same as the curvature of the curve obtained by intersecting the surface with the plane containing **T** and **u**.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Taking all possible tangent vectors, the maximum and minimum values of the normal curvature at a point are called the **principal curvatures**, *k*1 and *k*2, and the directions of the corresponding tangent vectors are called **principal normal directions**.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Curvature can be evaluated along surface normal sections, similar to § Curves on surfaces above (see for example the Earth radius of curvature).
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Some curved surfaces, such as those made from a smooth sheet of paper, can be flattened down into the plane without distorting their intrinsic features in any way.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Such developable surfaces have zero Gaussian curvature (see below).
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] In contrast to curves, which do not have intrinsic curvature, but do have extrinsic curvature (they only have a curvature given an embedding), surfaces can have intrinsic curvature, independent of an embedding.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] The Gaussian curvature, named after Carl Friedrich Gauss, is equal to the product of the principal curvatures, *k*1*k*2.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] It has a dimension of length−2 and is positive for spheres, negative for one-sheet hyperboloids and zero for planes and cylinders.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] It determines whether a surface is locally convex (when it is positive) or locally saddle-shaped (when it is negative).
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Gaussian curvature is an *intrinsic* property of the surface, meaning it does not depend on the particular embedding of the surface; intuitively, this means that ants living on the surface could determine the Gaussian curvature.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] For example, an ant living on a sphere could measure the sum of the interior angles of a triangle and determine that it was greater than 180 degrees, implying that the space it inhabited had positive curvature.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] On the other hand, an ant living on a cylinder would not detect any such departure from Euclidean geometry; in particular the ant could not detect that the two surfaces have different mean curvatures (see below), which is a purely extrinsic type of curvature.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Formally, Gaussian curvature only depends on the Riemannian metric of the surface.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] This is Gauss's celebrated Theorema Egregium, which he found while concerned with geographic surveys and mapmaking.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] An intrinsic definition of the Gaussian curvature at a point P is the following: imagine an ant which is tied to P with a short thread of length r.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] It runs around P while the thread is completely stretched and measures the length *C*(*r*) of one complete trip around P.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] If the surface were flat, the ant would find *C*(*r*) = 2π*r*.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] The integral of the Gaussian curvature over the whole surface is closely related to the surface's Euler characteristic; see the Gauss–Bonnet theorem.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] The discrete analog of curvature, corresponding to curvature being concentrated at a point and particularly useful for polyhedra, is the (angular) defect; the analog for the Gauss–Bonnet theorem is Descartes' theorem on total angular defect.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Because (Gaussian) curvature can be defined without reference to an embedding space, it is not necessary that a surface be embedded in a higher-dimensional space in order to be curved.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Such an intrinsically curved two-dimensional surface is a simple example of a Riemannian manifold.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] The mean curvature is an *extrinsic* measure of curvature equal to half the sum of the principal curvatures, ⁠*k*1 + *k*2/2⁠.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] It was introduced by Sophie Germain in her work on elasticity theory.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Mean curvature is closely related to the first variation of surface area.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] In particular, a minimal surface such as a soap film has mean curvature zero and a soap bubble has constant mean curvature.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Unlike Gauss curvature, the mean curvature is extrinsic and depends on the embedding, for instance, a cylinder and a plane are locally isometric but the mean curvature of a plane is zero while that of a cylinder is nonzero.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] The intrinsic and extrinsic curvature of a surface can be combined in the second fundamental form.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] where **N** is the unit normal to the surface.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] For unit tangent vectors **X**, the second fundamental form assumes the maximum value *k*1 and minimum value *k*2, which occur in the principal directions **u**1 and **u**2, respectively.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Thus the second fundamental form encodes both the intrinsic and extrinsic curvatures.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] An encapsulation of surface curvature can be found in the shape operator, *S*, which is a self-adjoint linear operator from the tangent plane to itself (specifically, the differential of the Gauss map).
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] The principal curvatures are the eigenvalues of the shape operator, the principal curvature directions are its eigenvectors, the Gauss curvature is its determinant, and the mean curvature is half its trace.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] By extension of the former argument, a space of three or more dimensions can be intrinsically curved.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] The curvature is *intrinsic* in the sense that it is a property defined at every point in the space, rather than a property defined with respect to a larger space that contains it.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] In general, a curved space may or may not be conceived as being embedded in a higher-dimensional ambient space; if not then its curvature can only be defined intrinsically.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] In the theory of general relativity, which describes gravity and cosmology, the idea is slightly generalised to the "curvature of spacetime"; in relativity theory spacetime is a pseudo-Riemannian manifold.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Once a time coordinate is defined, the three-dimensional space corresponding to a particular time is generally a curved Riemannian manifold; but since the time coordinate choice is largely arbitrary, it is the underlying spacetime curvature that is physically significant.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] A positive curvature corresponds to the inverse square radius of curvature; an example is a sphere or hypersphere.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] An example of negatively curved space is hyperbolic geometry (see also: non-positive curvature).
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] A space or space-time with zero curvature is called ***flat***.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] For example, Euclidean space is an example of a flat space, and Minkowski space is an example of a flat spacetime.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] There are other examples of flat geometries in both settings, though.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] A torus or a cylinder can both be given flat metrics, but differ in their topology.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Other topologies are also possible for curved space .
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] The mathematical notion of *curvature* is also defined in much more general contexts.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Many of these generalizations emphasize different aspects of the curvature as it is understood in lower dimensions.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] The curvature of a curve can naturally be considered as a kinematic quantity, representing the force felt by a certain observer moving along the curve; analogously, curvature in higher dimensions can be regarded as a kind of tidal force (this is one way of thinking of the sectional curvature).
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] This generalization of curvature depends on how nearby test particles diverge or converge when they are allowed to move freely in the space; see Jacobi field.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Another broad generalization of curvature comes from the study of parallel transport on a surface.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] For instance, if a vector is moved around a loop on the surface of a sphere keeping parallel throughout the motion, then the final position of the vector may not be the same as the initial position of the vector.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Various generalizations capture in an abstract form this idea of curvature as a measure of holonomy; see curvature form.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] A closely related notion of curvature comes from gauge theory in physics, where the curvature represents a field and a vector potential for the field is a quantity that is in general path-dependent: it may change if an observer moves around a loop.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Two more generalizations of curvature are the scalar curvature and Ricci curvature.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] In a curved surface such as the sphere, the area of a disc on the surface differs from the area of a disc of the same radius in flat space.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] This difference (in a suitable limit) is measured by the scalar curvature.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] The difference in area of a sector of the disc is measured by the Ricci curvature.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Each of the scalar curvature and Ricci curvature are defined in analogous ways in three and higher dimensions.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] They are particularly important in relativity theory, where they both appear on the side of Einstein's field equations that represents the geometry of spacetime (the other side of which represents the presence of matter and energy).
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] These generalizations of curvature underlie, for instance, the notion that curvature can be a property of a measure; see curvature of a measure.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Another generalization of curvature relies on the ability to compare a curved space with another space that has *constant* curvature.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] Often this is done with triangles in the spaces.
[src:differential-geometry/curvature] The notion of a triangle makes senses in metric spaces, and this gives rise to CAT(*k*) spaces.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] In mathematics, a **differentiable manifold** (also **differential manifold**) is a type of manifold that is locally similar enough to a vector space to allow one to apply calculus.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Any manifold can be described by a collection of charts (atlas).
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] One may then apply ideas from calculus while working within the individual charts, since each chart lies within a vector space to which the usual rules of calculus apply.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] If the charts are suitably compatible (namely, the transition from one chart to another is differentiable), then computations done in one chart are valid in any other differentiable chart.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] In formal terms, a **differentiable manifold** is a topological manifold with a globally defined differential structure.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Any topological manifold can be given a differential structure locally by using the homeomorphisms in its atlas and the standard differential structure on a vector space.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] To induce a global differential structure on the local coordinate systems induced by the homeomorphisms, their compositions on chart intersections in the atlas must be differentiable functions on the corresponding vector space.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] In other words, where the domains of charts overlap, the coordinates defined by each chart are required to be differentiable with respect to the coordinates defined by every chart in the atlas.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] The ability to define such a local differential structure on an abstract space allows one to extend the definition of differentiability to spaces without global coordinate systems.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] A locally differential structure allows one to define the globally differentiable tangent space, differentiable functions, and differentiable tensor and vector fields.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Differentiable manifolds are very important in physics.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Special kinds of differentiable manifolds form the basis for physical theories such as classical mechanics, general relativity, and Yang–Mills theory.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] It is possible to develop a calculus for differentiable manifolds.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] This leads to such mathematical machinery as the exterior calculus.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] The study of calculus on differentiable manifolds is known as differential geometry.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] "Differentiability" of a manifold has been given several meanings, including: continuously differentiable, *k*-times differentiable, smooth (which itself has many meanings), and analytic.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] The emergence of differential geometry as a distinct discipline is generally credited to Carl Friedrich Gauss and Bernhard Riemann.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Riemann first described manifolds in his famous habilitation lecture before the faculty at Göttingen.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Having constructed the notion of a manifoldness of n dimensions, and found that its true character consists in the property that the determination of position in it may be reduced to n determinations of magnitude, ...
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] These ideas found a key application in Albert Einstein's theory of general relativity and its underlying equivalence principle.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] A modern definition of a 2-dimensional manifold was given by Hermann Weyl in his 1913 book on Riemann surfaces.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] The widely accepted general definition of a manifold in terms of an atlas is due to Hassler Whitney.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] A **chart** (*U*, *φ*) on M consists of an open subset U of M, and a homeomorphism *φ* from U to an open subset of some Euclidean space **R***n*.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Somewhat informally, one may refer to a chart *φ* : *U* → **R***n*, meaning that the image of φ is an open subset of **R***n*, and that φ is a homeomorphism onto its image; in the usage of some authors, this may instead mean that *φ* : *U* → **R***n* is itself a homeomorphism.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] This situation is not fully satisfactory for the following reason.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Consider a second chart (*V*, *ψ*) on M, and suppose that U and V contain some points in common.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Since φ and *ψ* are homeomorphisms, it follows that *ψ* ∘ *φ*−1 is a homeomorphism from *φ*(*U* ∩ *V*) to *ψ*(*U* ∩ *V*).
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] The same problem is found if one considers instead functions *c* : **R** → *M*; one is led to the reparametrization formula $\varphi \circ c={\big (}\varphi \circ \psi ^{-1}{\big )}\circ {\big (}\psi \circ c{\big )},$ at which point one can make the same observation as before.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] This is resolved by the introduction of a "differentiable atlas" of charts, which specifies a collection of charts on M for which the transition maps *ψ* ∘ *φ*−1 are all differentiable.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] This makes the situation quite clean: if *u* ∘ *φ*−1 is differentiable, then due to the first reparametrization formula listed above, the map *u* ∘ *ψ*−1 is also differentiable on the region *ψ*(*U* ∩ *V*), and vice versa.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Moreover, the derivatives of these two maps are linked to one another by the chain rule.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Relative to the given atlas, this facilitates a notion of differentiable mappings whose domain or range is M, as well as a notion of the derivative of such maps.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Formally, the word "differentiable" is somewhat ambiguous, as it is taken to mean different things by different authors; sometimes it means the existence of first derivatives, sometimes the existence of continuous first derivatives, and sometimes the existence of infinitely many derivatives.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] The following gives a formal definition of various (nonambiguous) meanings of "differentiable atlas".
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Generally, "differentiable" will be used as a catch-all term including all of these possibilities, provided *k* ≥ 1.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Since every real-analytic map is smooth, and every smooth map is *C**k* for any k, one can see that any analytic atlas can also be viewed as a smooth atlas, and every smooth atlas can be viewed as a *C**k* atlas.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] This chain can be extended to include holomorphic atlases, with the understanding that any holomorphic map between open subsets of **C***n* can be viewed as a real-analytic map between open subsets of **R**2*n*.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] A differentiable atlas determines a **maximal differentiable atlas**, consisting of all charts which are differentiably compatible with the given atlas.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] For instance, given any chart in a maximal atlas, its restriction to an arbitrary open subset of its domain will also be contained in the maximal atlas.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] A maximal smooth atlas is also known as a smooth structure; a maximal holomorphic atlas is also known as a complex structure.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] An alternative but equivalent definition, avoiding the direct use of maximal atlases, is to consider equivalence classes of differentiable atlases, in which two differentiable atlases are considered equivalent if every chart of one atlas is differentiably compatible with the other atlas.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Informally, what this means is that in dealing with a smooth manifold, one can work with a single differentiable atlas, consisting of only a few charts, with the implicit understanding that many other charts and differentiable atlases are equally legitimate.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] According to the invariance of domain, each connected component of a topological space which has a differentiable atlas has a well-defined dimension n.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] This causes a small ambiguity in the case of a holomorphic atlas, since the corresponding dimension will be one-half of the value of its dimension when considered as an analytic, smooth, or *C**k* atlas.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] For this reason, one refers separately to the "real" and "complex" dimension of a topological space with a holomorphic atlas.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] A **differentiable manifold** is a Hausdorff and second countable topological space M, together with a maximal differentiable atlas on M.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Much of the basic theory can be developed without the need for the Hausdorff and second countability conditions, although they are vital for much of the advanced theory.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] They are essentially equivalent to the general existence of bump functions and partitions of unity, both of which are used ubiquitously.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] The notion of a *C*0 manifold is identical to that of a topological manifold.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] However, there is a notable distinction to be made.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Given a topological space, it is meaningful to ask whether or not it is a topological manifold.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] By contrast, it is not meaningful to ask whether or not a given topological space is (for instance) a smooth manifold, since the notion of a smooth manifold requires the specification of a smooth atlas, which is an additional structure.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] It could, however, be meaningful to say that a certain topological space cannot be given the structure of a smooth manifold.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] It is possible to reformulate the definitions so that this sort of imbalance is not present; one can start with a set M (rather than a topological space M), using the natural analogue of a smooth atlas in this setting to define the structure of a topological space on M.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] One can reverse-engineer the above definitions to obtain one perspective on the construction of manifolds.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] The idea is to start with the images of the charts and the transition maps, and to construct the manifold purely from this data.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] As in the above discussion, we use the "smooth" context but everything works just as well in other settings.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Given an indexing set $A,$ let $V_{\alpha }$ be a collection of open subsets of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ and for each $\alpha ,\beta \in A$ let $V_{\alpha \beta }$ be an open (possibly empty) subset of $V_{\beta }$ and let $\phi _{\alpha \beta }:V_{\alpha \beta }\to V_{\beta \alpha }$ be a smooth map.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Suppose that $\phi _{\alpha \alpha }$ is the identity map, that $\phi _{\alpha \beta }\circ \phi _{\beta \alpha }$ is the identity map, and that $\phi _{\alpha \beta }\circ \phi _{\beta \gamma }\circ \phi _{\gamma \alpha }$ is the identity map.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] For the patching together the analytic structures(subset), see analytic varieties.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] A real valued function *f* on an *n*-dimensional differentiable manifold *M* is called **differentiable** at a point *p* ∈ *M* if it is differentiable in any coordinate chart defined around *p*.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] In general, there will be many available charts; however, the definition of differentiability does not depend on the choice of chart at *p*.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] It follows from the chain rule applied to the transition functions between one chart and another that if *f* is differentiable in any particular chart at *p*, then it is differentiable in all charts at *p*.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Analogous considerations apply to defining *Ck* functions, smooth functions, and analytic functions.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] There are various ways to define the derivative of a function on a differentiable manifold, the most fundamental of which is the directional derivative.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] The definition of the directional derivative is complicated by the fact that a manifold will lack a suitable affine structure with which to define vectors.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Therefore, the directional derivative looks at curves in the manifold instead of vectors.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Given a real valued function *f* on an *n* dimensional differentiable manifold *M*, the directional derivative of *f* at a point *p* in *M* is defined as follows.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Suppose that γ(*t*) is a curve in *M* with *γ*(0) = *p*, which is *differentiable* in the sense that its composition with any chart is a differentiable curve in **R***n*.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] then, by the chain rule, *f* has the same directional derivative at *p* along *γ*1 as along *γ*2.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] This means that the directional derivative depends only on the tangent vector of the curve at *p*.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Thus, the more abstract definition of directional differentiation adapted to the case of differentiable manifolds ultimately captures the intuitive features of directional differentiation in an affine space.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] A **tangent vector** at *p* ∈ *M* is an equivalence class of differentiable curves *γ* with *γ*(0) = *p*, modulo the equivalence relation of first-order contact between the curves.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Therefore, the equivalence classes are curves through *p* with a prescribed velocity vector at *p*.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] The collection of all tangent vectors at *p* forms a vector space: the tangent space to *M* at *p*, denoted *T**p**M*.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] If the function *f* is fixed, then the mapping $X\mapsto Xf(p)$ is a linear functional on the tangent space.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] One can check that $T_{p}M$ naturally has the structure of a n -dimensional real vector space, and that with this structure, $df_{p}$ is a linear map.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] With the idea of the formal definitions understood, this shorthand notation is, for most purposes, much easier to work with.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] One of the topological features of the sheaf of differentiable functions on a differentiable manifold is that it admits partitions of unity.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] This distinguishes the differential structure on a manifold from stronger structures (such as analytic and holomorphic structures) that in general fail to have partitions of unity.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Suppose that *M* is a manifold of class *Ck*, where 0 ≤ *k* ≤ ∞.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Let {*U**α*} be an open covering of *M*.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Every open covering of a *Ck* manifold *M* has a *Ck* partition of unity.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] This allows for certain constructions from the topology of *Ck* functions on **R***n* to be carried over to the category of differentiable manifolds.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] In particular, it is possible to discuss integration by choosing a partition of unity subordinate to a particular coordinate atlas, and carrying out the integration in each chart of **R***n*.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Partitions of unity therefore allow for certain other kinds of function spaces to be considered: for instance L*p* spaces, Sobolev spaces, and other kinds of spaces that require integration.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Suppose *M* and *N* are two differentiable manifolds with dimensions *m* and *n*, respectively, and *f* is a function from *M* to *N*.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Since differentiable manifolds are topological spaces we know what it means for *f* to be continuous.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] We know what that means when *f* is a function between Euclidean spaces, so if we compose *f* with a chart of *M* and a chart of *N* such that we get a map that goes from Euclidean space to *M* to *N* to Euclidean space we know what it means for that map to be *Ck*(**R***m*, **R***n*).
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Once again, the chain rule guarantees that the idea of differentiability does not depend on which charts of the atlases on *M* and *N* are selected.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] However, defining the derivative itself is more subtle.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] If *M* or *N* is itself already a Euclidean space, then we don't need a chart to map it to one.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] The tangent space of a point consists of the possible directional derivatives at that point, and has the same dimension *n* as does the manifold.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] For a set of (non-singular) coordinates *xk* local to the point, the coordinate derivatives $\partial _{k}={\frac {\partial }{\partial x_{k}}}$ define a holonomic basis of the tangent space.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] The collection of tangent spaces at all points can in turn be made into a manifold, the tangent bundle, whose dimension is 2*n*.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] The tangent bundle is where tangent vectors lie, and is itself a differentiable manifold.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] The Lagrangian is a function on the tangent bundle.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] One can also define the tangent bundle as the bundle of 1-jets from **R** (the real line) to *M*.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] One may construct an atlas for the tangent bundle consisting of charts based on *U**α* × **R***n*, where *U**α* denotes one of the charts in the atlas for *M*.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Each of these new charts is the tangent bundle for the charts *U**α*.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] The transition maps on this atlas are defined from the transition maps on the original manifold, and retain the original differentiability class.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] The dual space of a vector space is the set of real valued linear functions on the vector space.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] The cotangent space at a point is the dual of the tangent space at that point and the elements are referred to as cotangent vectors; the cotangent bundle is the collection of all cotangent vectors, along with the natural differentiable manifold structure.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Like the tangent bundle, the cotangent bundle is again a differentiable manifold.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] The Hamiltonian is a scalar on the cotangent bundle.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] The total space of a cotangent bundle has the structure of a symplectic manifold.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Cotangent vectors are sometimes called *covectors*.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] One can also define the cotangent bundle as the bundle of 1-jets of functions from *M* to **R**.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Elements of the cotangent space can be thought of as infinitesimal displacements: if *f* is a differentiable function we can define at each point *p* a cotangent vector *dfp*, which sends a tangent vector *Xp* to the derivative of *f* associated with *Xp*.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] However, not every covector field can be expressed this way.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Those that can are referred to as exact differentials.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] For a given set of local coordinates *xk,* the differentials *dx**k* *p* form a basis of the cotangent space at *p*.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] The tensor bundle is the direct sum of all tensor products of the tangent bundle and the cotangent bundle.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Each element of the bundle is a tensor field, which can act as a multilinear operator on vector fields, or on other tensor fields.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] The tensor bundle is not a differentiable manifold in the traditional sense, since it is infinite dimensional.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] It is however an algebra over the ring of scalar functions.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Each tensor is characterized by its ranks, which indicate how many tangent and cotangent factors it has.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Sometimes these ranks are referred to as *covariant* and *contravariant* ranks, signifying tangent and cotangent ranks, respectively.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] A frame (or, in more precise terms, a tangent frame), is an ordered basis of particular tangent space.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Likewise, a tangent frame is a linear isomorphism of **R***n* to this tangent space.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] A moving tangent frame is an ordered list of vector fields that give a basis at every point of their domain.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] One may also regard a moving frame as a section of the frame bundle F(*M*), a GL(*n*, **R**) principal bundle made up of the set of all frames over *M*.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] The frame bundle is useful because tensor fields on *M* can be regarded as equivariant vector-valued functions on F(*M*).
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] On a manifold that is sufficiently smooth, various kinds of jet bundles can also be considered.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] The (first-order) tangent bundle of a manifold is the collection of curves in the manifold modulo the equivalence relation of first-order contact.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] By analogy, the *k*-th order tangent bundle is the collection of curves modulo the relation of *k*-th order contact.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Likewise, the cotangent bundle is the bundle of 1-jets of functions on the manifold: the *k*-jet bundle is the bundle of their *k*-jets.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] These and other examples of the general idea of jet bundles play a significant role in the study of differential operators on manifolds.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] The notion of a frame also generalizes to the case of higher-order jets.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Define a *k*-th order frame to be the *k*-jet of a diffeomorphism from **R***n* to *M*.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] The collection of all *k*-th order frames, *Fk*(*M*), is a principal *Gk* bundle over *M*, where *Gk* is the group of *k*-jets; i.e., the group made up of *k*-jets of diffeomorphisms of **R***n* that fix the origin.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Note that GL(*n*, **R**) is naturally isomorphic to *G*1, and a subgroup of every *Gk*, *k* ≥ 2.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] In particular, a section of *F*2(*M*) gives the frame components of a connection on *M*.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Thus, the quotient bundle *F*2(*M*) / GL(*n*, **R**) is the bundle of *symmetric* linear connections over *M*.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Many of the techniques from multivariate calculus also apply, *mutatis mutandis*, to differentiable manifolds.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] One can define the directional derivative of a differentiable function along a tangent vector to the manifold, for instance, and this leads to a means of generalizing the total derivative of a function: the differential.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] From the perspective of calculus, the derivative of a function on a manifold behaves in much the same way as the ordinary derivative of a function defined on a Euclidean space, at least locally.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] For example, there are versions of the implicit and inverse function theorems for such functions.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] There are, however, important differences in the calculus of vector fields (and tensor fields in general).
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] In brief, the directional derivative of a vector field is not well-defined, or at least not defined in a straightforward manner.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Several generalizations of the derivative of a vector field (or tensor field) do exist, and capture certain formal features of differentiation in Euclidean spaces.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Ideas from integral calculus also carry over to differential manifolds.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] These are naturally expressed in the language of exterior calculus and differential forms.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] The fundamental theorems of integral calculus in several variables—namely Green's theorem, the divergence theorem, and Stokes' theorem—generalize to a theorem (also called Stokes' theorem) relating the exterior derivative and integration over submanifolds.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Differentiable functions between two manifolds are needed in order to formulate suitable notions of submanifolds, and other related concepts.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] If *f* : *M* → *N* is a differentiable function from a differentiable manifold *M* of dimension *m* to another differentiable manifold *N* of dimension *n*, then the differential of *f* is a mapping *df* : T*M* → T*N*.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] It is also denoted by *Tf* and called the **tangent map**.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] At each point of *M*, this is a linear transformation from one tangent space to another: $df(p)\colon T_{p}M\to T_{f(p)}N.$ The **rank** of *f* at *p* is the rank of this linear transformation.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Usually the rank of a function is a pointwise property.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] However, if the function has maximal rank, then the rank will remain constant in a neighborhood of a point.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] A differentiable function "usually" has maximal rank, in a precise sense given by Sard's theorem.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] A Lie derivative, named after Sophus Lie, is a derivation on the algebra of tensor fields over a manifold *M*.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] The Lie derivatives are represented by vector fields, as infinitesimal generators of flows (active diffeomorphisms) on *M*.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Looking at it the other way around, the group of diffeomorphisms of *M* has the associated Lie algebra structure, of Lie derivatives, in a way directly analogous to the Lie group theory.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] The exterior calculus allows for a generalization of the gradient, divergence and curl operators.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] The bundle of differential forms, at each point, consists of all totally antisymmetric multilinear maps on the tangent space at that point.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] It is naturally divided into *n*-forms for each *n* at most equal to the dimension of the manifold; an *n*-form is an *n*-variable form, also called a form of degree *n*.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] The 1-forms are the cotangent vectors, while the 0-forms are just scalar functions.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] In general, an *n*-form is a tensor with cotangent rank *n* and tangent rank 0.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] But not every such tensor is a form, as a form must be antisymmetric.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] The *exterior derivative* is a linear operator on the graded vector space of all smooth differential forms on a smooth manifold M .
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] More precisely, if $n=\dim(M)$ , for $0\leq k\leq n$ the operator d maps the space $\Omega ^{k}(M)$ of k -forms on M into the space $\Omega ^{k+1}(M)$ of $(k+1)$ -forms (if $k>n$ there are no non-zero k -forms on M so the map d is identically zero on n -forms).
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] The exterior derivative also satisfies the identity $d\circ d=0$ .
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] That is, if $\omega$ is a k -form then the $(k+2)$ -form $d(df)$ is identically vanishing.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] A form $\omega$ such that $d\omega =0$ is called *closed*, while a form $\omega$ such that $\omega =d\eta$ for some other form $\eta$ is called *exact*.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Another formulation of the identity $d\circ d=0$ is that an exact form is closed.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] This allows one to define de Rham cohomology of the manifold M , where the k th cohomology group is the quotient group of the closed forms on M by the exact forms on M .
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Suppose that M is a topological n -manifold.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Then consider the new atlas $\{(\Phi ^{-1}(U_{\alpha }),\phi _{\alpha }\circ \Phi )\}_{\alpha \in A},$ which is easily verified as a smooth atlas.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] More briefly, one could say that two smooth atlases are equivalent if there exists a diffeomorphism $M\to M,$ in which one smooth atlas is taken for the domain and the other smooth atlas is taken for the range.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Note that this equivalence relation is a refinement of the equivalence relation which defines a smooth manifold structure, as any two smoothly compatible atlases are also compatible in the present sense; one can take $\Phi$ to be the identity map.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] If the dimension of M is 1, 2, or 3, then there exists a smooth structure on M , and all distinct smooth structures are equivalent in the above sense.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] The situation is more complicated in higher dimensions, although it isn't fully understood.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Every one-dimensional connected smooth manifold is diffeomorphic to either $\mathbb {R}$ or $S^{1},$ each with their standard smooth structures.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] For a classification of smooth 2-manifolds, see surface.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] The situation in three dimensions is quite a bit more complicated, and known results are more indirect.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] A remarkable result, proved in 2002 by methods of partial differential equations, is the geometrization conjecture, stating loosely that any compact smooth 3-manifold can be split up into different parts, each of which admits Riemannian metrics which possess many symmetries.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] There are also various "recognition results" for geometrizable 3-manifolds, such as Mostow rigidity and Sela's algorithm for the isomorphism problem for hyperbolic groups.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] The classification of *n*-manifolds for *n* greater than three is known to be impossible, even up to homotopy equivalence.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Given any finitely presented group, one can construct a closed 4-manifold having that group as fundamental group.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Since there is no algorithm to decide the isomorphism problem for finitely presented groups, there is no algorithm to decide whether two 4-manifolds have the same fundamental group.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Since the previously described construction results in a class of 4-manifolds that are homeomorphic if and only if their groups are isomorphic, the homeomorphism problem for 4-manifolds is undecidable.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] In addition, since even recognizing the trivial group is undecidable, it is not even possible in general to decide whether a manifold has trivial fundamental group, i.e. is simply connected.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Simply connected 4-manifolds have been classified up to homeomorphism by Freedman using the intersection form and Kirby–Siebenmann invariant.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Smooth 4-manifold theory is known to be much more complicated, as the exotic smooth structures on **R**4 demonstrate.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] However, the situation becomes more tractable for simply connected smooth manifolds of dimension ≥ 5, where the h-cobordism theorem can be used to reduce the classification to a classification up to homotopy equivalence, and surgery theory can be applied.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] This has been carried out to provide an explicit classification of simply connected 5-manifolds by Dennis Barden.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] A Riemannian manifold consists of a smooth manifold together with a positive-definite inner product on each of the individual tangent spaces.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] This collection of inner products is called the Riemannian metric, and is naturally a symmetric 2-tensor field.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] This "metric" identifies a natural vector space isomorphism $T_{p}M\to T_{p}^{\ast }M$ for each $p\in M.$ On a Riemannian manifold one can define notions of length, volume, and angle.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Any smooth manifold can be given many different Riemannian metrics.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] A pseudo-Riemannian manifold (also called a semi-Riemannian manifold) is a generalization of the notion of Riemannian manifold where the inner products are allowed to have an indefinite signature, as opposed to being positive-definite; they are still required to be non-degenerate.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Every smooth pseudo-Riemannian and Riemmannian manifold defines a number of associated tensor fields, such as the Riemann curvature tensor.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Lorentzian manifolds are pseudo-Riemannian manifolds of signature $(n-1,1)$ ; the case $n=4$ is fundamental in general relativity.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] Not every smooth manifold can be given a non-Riemannian pseudo-Riemannian structure; there are topological restrictions on doing so.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] A Finsler manifold is a different generalization of a Riemannian manifold, in which the inner product is replaced with a vector norm; as such, this allows the definition of length, but not angle.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] A symplectic manifold is a manifold equipped with a closed, nondegenerate 2-form.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] This condition forces symplectic manifolds to be even-dimensional, due to the fact that skew-symmetric $(2n+1)\times (2n+1)$ matrices all have zero determinant.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] A Lie group consists of a *C*∞ manifold G together with a group structure on G such that the product and inversion maps $m:G\times G\to G$ and $i:G\to G$ are smooth as maps of manifolds.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] These objects often arise naturally in describing (continuous) symmetries, and they form an important source of examples of smooth manifolds.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] In particular, by considering an arbitrary nonzero vector in $T_{e}G,$ one can use these identifications to give a smooth non-vanishing vector field on $G.$ This shows, for instance, that no even-dimensional sphere can support a Lie group structure.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p01] The same argument shows, more generally, that every Lie group must be parallelizable.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] The notion of a pseudogroup provides a flexible generalization of atlases in order to allow a variety of different structures to be defined on manifolds in a uniform way.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] If *f* is a homeomorphism from a union of open subsets of *S*, $\cup _{i}\,U_{i}$ , to an open subset of *S*, then *f* ∈ Γ provided $f|_{U_{i}}\in \Gamma$ for every *i*.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] For every open *U* ⊂ *S*, the identity transformation of *U* is in Γ.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] The composition of two elements of Γ is in Γ.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] These last three conditions are analogous to the definition of a group.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] Note that Γ need not be a group, however, since the functions are not globally defined on *S*.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] For example, the collection of all local *Ck* diffeomorphisms on **R***n* form a pseudogroup.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] All biholomorphisms between open sets in **C***n* form a pseudogroup.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] More examples include: orientation preserving maps of **R***n*, symplectomorphisms, Möbius transformations, affine transformations, and so on.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] Thus, a wide variety of function classes determine pseudogroups.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] An atlas (*Ui*, *φ**i*) of homeomorphisms *φ**i* from *Ui* ⊂ *M* to open subsets of a topological space *S* is said to be *compatible* with a pseudogroup Γ provided that the transition functions *φ**j* ∘ *φ**i*−1 : *φ**i*(*Ui* ∩ *Uj*) → *φ**j*(*Ui* ∩ *Uj*) are all in Γ.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] A differentiable manifold is then an atlas compatible with the pseudogroup of *C**k* functions on **R***n*.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] A complex manifold is an atlas compatible with the biholomorphic functions on open sets in **C***n*.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] Thus, pseudogroups provide a single framework in which to describe many structures on manifolds of importance to differential geometry and topology.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] Sometimes, it can be useful to use an alternative approach to endow a manifold with a *Ck*-structure.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] Here *k* = 1, 2, ..., ∞, or ω for real analytic manifolds.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] Instead of considering coordinate charts, it is possible to start with functions defined on the manifold itself.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] The structure sheaf of *M*, denoted **C***k*, is a sort of functor that defines, for each open set *U* ⊂ *M*, an algebra **C***k*(*U*) of continuous functions *U* → **R**.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] In particular, this latter condition means that any function *h* in **C***k*(*V*), for *V*, can be written uniquely as *h*(*x*) = *H*(*x*1(*x*), ..., *x**n*(*x*)), where *H* is a *k*-times differentiable function on *f*(*V*) (an open set in **R***n*).
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] Thus, the sheaf-theoretic viewpoint is that the functions on a differentiable manifold can be expressed in local coordinates as differentiable functions on **R***n*, and *a fortiori* this is sufficient to characterize the differential structure on the manifold.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] A similar, but more technical, approach to defining differentiable manifolds can be formulated using the notion of a ringed space.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] This approach is strongly influenced by the theory of schemes in algebraic geometry, but uses local rings of the germs of differentiable functions.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] It is especially popular in the context of *complex* manifolds.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] We begin by describing the basic structure sheaf on **R***n*.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] consist of all real-valued *k*-times continuously differentiable functions on *U*.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] As *U* varies, this determines a sheaf of rings on **R**n.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] The stalk **O***p* for *p* ∈ **R***n* consists of germs of functions near *p*, and is an algebra over **R**.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] In particular, this is a local ring whose unique maximal ideal consists of those functions that vanish at *p*.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] The pair (**R***n*, **O**) is an example of a locally ringed space: it is a topological space equipped with a sheaf whose stalks are each local rings.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] A differentiable manifold (of class *Ck*) consists of a pair (*M*, **O***M*) where *M* is a second countable Hausdorff space, and **O***M* is a sheaf of local **R**-algebras defined on *M*, such that the locally ringed space (*M*, **O***M*) is locally isomorphic to (**R***n*, **O**).
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] In this way, differentiable manifolds can be thought of as schemes modeled on **R***n*.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] There are a number of important motivations for studying differentiable manifolds within this abstract framework.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] First, there is no *a priori* reason that the model space needs to be **R**n.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] In broader terms, this concept can be adapted for any suitable notion of a scheme (see topos theory).
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] Second, coordinates are no longer explicitly necessary to the construction.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] The analog of a coordinate system is the pair (*f*, *f*#), but these merely quantify the idea of *local isomorphism* rather than being central to the discussion (as in the case of charts and atlases).
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] Third, the sheaf **O***M* is not manifestly a sheaf of functions at all.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] Rather, it emerges as a sheaf of functions as a *consequence* of the construction (via the quotients of local rings by their maximal ideals).
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] Hence, it is a more primitive definition of the structure (see synthetic differential geometry).
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] A final advantage of this approach is that it allows for natural direct descriptions of many of the fundamental objects of study to differential geometry and topology.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] The category of smooth manifolds with smooth maps lacks certain desirable properties, and people have tried to generalize smooth manifolds in order to rectify this.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] Diffeological spaces use a different notion of chart known as a "plot".
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] Frölicher spaces and orbifolds are other attempts.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] A rectifiable set generalizes the idea of a piece-wise smooth or rectifiable curve to higher dimensions; however, rectifiable sets are not in general manifolds.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] Banach manifolds and Fréchet manifolds, in particular manifolds of mappings are infinite dimensional differentiable manifolds.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] For a *Ck* manifold *M*, the set of real-valued *Ck* functions on the manifold forms an algebra under pointwise addition and multiplication, called the *algebra of scalar fields* or simply the *algebra of scalars*.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] This algebra has the constant function 1 as the multiplicative identity, and is a differentiable analog of the ring of regular functions in algebraic geometry.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] It is possible to reconstruct a manifold from its algebra of scalars, first as a set, but also as a topological space – this is an application of the Banach–Stone theorem, and is more formally known as the spectrum of a C*-algebra.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] First, there is a one-to-one correspondence between the points of *M* and the algebra homomorphisms *φ*: *Ck*(*M*) → **R**, as such a homomorphism *φ* corresponds to a codimension one ideal in *Ck*(*M*) (namely the kernel of *φ*), which is necessarily a maximal ideal.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] On the converse, every maximal ideal in this algebra is an ideal of functions vanishing at a single point, which demonstrates that MSpec (the Max Spec) of *Ck*(*M*) recovers *M* as a point set, though in fact it recovers *M* as a topological space.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] One can define various geometric structures algebraically in terms of the algebra of scalars, and these definitions often generalize to algebraic geometry (interpreting rings geometrically) and operator theory (interpreting Banach spaces geometrically).
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] For example, the tangent bundle to *M* can be defined as the derivations of the algebra of smooth functions on *M*.
[src:differential-geometry/differentiable-manifold-p02] This is the basis of the field of noncommutative geometry.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] In mathematics, **differential forms** provide a unified approach to define integrands over curves, surfaces, volumes, and higher-dimensional manifolds.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] The modern notion of differential forms was pioneered by Élie Cartan.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] It has many applications, especially in geometry, topology and physics.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Likewise, a **3-form** $f(x,y,z)\,dx\wedge dy\wedge dz$ represents a volume element that can be integrated over a region of space.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] In general, a k -form is an object that may be integrated over a k -dimensional manifold, and is homogeneous of degree k in the coordinate differentials $dx,dy,\ldots .$ On an n -dimensional manifold, a top-dimensional form ( n -form) is called a *volume form*.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] The differential forms form an alternating algebra.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] This implies that $dy\wedge dx=-dx\wedge dy$ and $dx\wedge dx=0.$ This alternating property reflects the orientation of the domain of integration.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] The exterior derivative is an operation on differential forms that, given a k -form $\varphi$ , produces a $(k+1)$ -form $d\varphi .$ This operation extends the differential of a function (a function can be considered as a 0 -form, and its differential is $df(x)=f'(x)\,dx$ ).
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] This allows expressing the fundamental theorem of calculus, the divergence theorem, Green's theorem, and Stokes' theorem as special cases of a single general result, the generalized Stokes theorem.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Differential 1 -forms are naturally dual to vector fields on a differentiable manifold, and the pairing between vector fields and 1 -forms is extended to arbitrary differential forms by the interior product.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] The algebra of differential forms along with the exterior derivative defined on it is preserved by the pullback under smooth functions between two manifolds.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] This feature allows geometrically invariant information to be moved from one space to another via the pullback, provided that the information is expressed in terms of differential forms.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] As an example, the change of variables formula for integration becomes a simple statement that an integral is preserved under pullback.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Differential forms are part of the field of differential geometry, influenced by linear algebra.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Although the notion of a differential is quite old, the initial attempt at an algebraic organization of differential forms is usually credited to Élie Cartan with reference to his 1899 paper.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Some aspects of the exterior algebra of differential forms appears in Hermann Grassmann's 1844 work, *Die Lineale Ausdehnungslehre, ein neuer Zweig der Mathematik (The Theory of Linear Extension, a New Branch of Mathematics)*.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Differential forms provide an approach to multivariable calculus that is independent of coordinates.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] A differential k-form can be integrated over an oriented manifold of dimension k.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] A differential 1-form can be thought of as measuring an infinitesimal oriented length, or 1-dimensional oriented density.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] A differential 2-form can be thought of as measuring an infinitesimal oriented area, or 2-dimensional oriented density.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Integration of differential forms is well-defined only on oriented manifolds.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] An example of a 1-dimensional manifold is an interval [*a*, *b*], and intervals can be given an orientation: they are positively oriented if *a* < *b*, and negatively oriented otherwise.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] That is: $\int _{b}^{a}f(x)\,dx=-\int _{a}^{b}f(x)\,dx.$ This gives a geometrical context to the conventions for one-dimensional integrals, that the sign changes when the orientation of the interval is reversed.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] A standard explanation of this in one-variable integration theory is that, when the limits of integration are in the opposite order (*b* < *a*), the increment *dx* is negative in the direction of integration.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] More generally, an m-form is an oriented density that can be integrated over an m-dimensional oriented manifold.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] In measure theory, by contrast, one interprets the integrand as a function f with respect to a measure μ and integrates over a subset A, without any notion of orientation; one writes ${\textstyle \int _{A}f\,d\mu =\int _{[a,b]}f\,d\mu }$ to indicate integration over a subset A.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] This is a minor distinction in one dimension, but becomes subtler on higher-dimensional manifolds; see below for details.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Making the notion of an oriented density precise, and thus of a differential form, involves the exterior algebra.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] The differentials of a set of coordinates, *dx*1, ..., *dx**n* can be used as a basis for all 1-forms.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Each of these represents a covector at each point on the manifold that may be thought of as measuring a small displacement in the corresponding coordinate direction.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] A general 1-form is a linear combination of these differentials at every point on the manifold: $f_{1}\,dx^{1}+\cdots +f_{n}\,dx^{n},$ where the *f**k* = *f**k*(*x*1, ... , *x**n*) are functions of all the coordinates.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] A differential 1-form is integrated along an oriented curve as a line integral.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] The expressions *dx**i* ∧ *dx**j*, where *i* < *j* can be used as a basis at every point on the manifold for all 2-forms.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] This may be thought of as an infinitesimal oriented square parallel to the *x**i*–*x**j*-plane.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] A general 2-form is a linear combination of these at every point on the manifold: ${\textstyle \sum _{1\leq i<j\leq n}f_{i,j}\,dx^{i}\wedge dx^{j}}$ , and it is integrated just like a surface integral.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] A fundamental operation defined on differential forms is the exterior product (the symbol is the wedge ∧).
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] This is similar to the cross product from vector calculus, in that it is an alternating product.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] because the square whose first side is *dx*1 and second side is *dx*2 is to be regarded as having the opposite orientation as the square whose first side is *dx*2 and whose second side is *dx*1.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] The exterior product allows higher-degree differential forms to be built out of lower-degree ones, in much the same way that the cross product in vector calculus allows one to compute the area vector of a parallelogram from vectors pointing up the two sides.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Alternating also implies that *dx**i* ∧ *dx**i* = 0, in the same way that the cross product of parallel vectors, whose magnitude is the area of the parallelogram spanned by those vectors, is zero.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] In higher dimensions, *dx**i*1 ∧ ⋅⋅⋅ ∧ *dx**i**m* = 0 if any two of the indices *i*1, ..., *i**m* are equal, in the same way that the "volume" enclosed by a parallelotope whose edge vectors are linearly dependent is zero.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Another useful notation is obtained by defining the set of all strictly increasing multi-indices of length k , in a space of dimension n , denoted ${\mathcal {J}}_{k,n}:=\{I=(i_{1},\ldots ,i_{k}):1\leq i_{1}<i_{2}<\cdots <i_{k}\leq n\}$ .
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Then locally (wherever the coordinates apply), $\{dx^{I}\}_{I\in {\mathcal {J}}_{k,n}}$ spans the space of differential k -forms in a manifold M of dimension n , when viewed as a module over the ring $C^{\infty }(M)$ of smooth functions on M .
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] By calculating the size of ${\mathcal {J}}_{k,n}$ combinatorially, the module of k -forms on an n -dimensional manifold, and in general space of k -covectors on an n -dimensional vector space, is n choose k : ${\textstyle |{\mathcal {J}}_{k,n}|={\binom {n}{k}}}$ .
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] This also demonstrates that there are no nonzero differential forms of degree greater than the dimension of the underlying manifold.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] In addition to the exterior product, there is also the exterior derivative operator d .
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] The exterior derivative of a differential form is a generalization of the differential of a function, in the sense that the exterior derivative of $f\in C^{\infty }(M)=\Omega ^{0}(M)$ is exactly the differential of f .
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] In $\mathbb {R} ^{3}$ , with the Hodge star operator, the exterior derivative corresponds to gradient, curl, and divergence, although this correspondence, like the cross product, does not generalize to higher dimensions, and should be treated with some caution.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] The exterior derivative itself applies in an arbitrary finite number of dimensions, and is a flexible and powerful tool with wide application in differential geometry, differential topology, and many areas in physics.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Of note, although the above definition of the exterior derivative was defined with respect to local coordinates, it can be defined in an entirely coordinate-free manner, as an antiderivation of degree 1 on the exterior algebra of differential forms.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] The benefit of this more general approach is that it allows for a natural coordinate-free approach to integrate on manifolds.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] It also allows for a natural generalization of the fundamental theorem of calculus, called the (generalized) Stokes' theorem, which is a central result in the theory of integration on manifolds.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Let U be an open set in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] A differential 0 -form ("zero-form") is defined to be a smooth function f on U – the set of which is denoted $C^{\infty }(U)$ .
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] In particular, if **v** = **e***j* is the jth coordinate vector then ∂**v** *f* is the partial derivative of f with respect to the jth coordinate vector, i.e., ∂*f* / ∂*x**j*, where *x*1, *x*2, ..., *x**n* are the coordinate vectors in U.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] for any vectors **v**, **w** and any real number c.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] At each point *p*, this linear map from **R***n* to **R** is denoted *df**p* and called the derivative or differential of f at p.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Extended over the whole set, the object *df* can be viewed as a function that takes a vector field on U, and returns a real-valued function whose value at each point is the derivative along the vector field of the function f.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Note that at each p, the differential *df**p* is not a real number, but a linear functional on tangent vectors, and a prototypical example of a differential 1-form.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Since any vector **v** is a linear combination Σ *v**j***e***j* of its components, *df* is uniquely determined by *df**p*(**e***j*) for each *j* and each *p* ∈ *U*, which are just the partial derivatives of f on U.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Thus *df* provides a way of encoding the partial derivatives of f.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] It can be decoded by noticing that the coordinates *x*1, *x*2, ..., *x**n* are themselves functions on U, and so define differential 1-forms *dx*1, *dx*2, ..., *dx**n*.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Since p and j were arbitrary, this proves the formula **(*)**.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] More generally, for any smooth functions *g**i* and *h**i* on U, we define the differential 1-form *α* = Σ*i* *g**i* *dh**i* pointwise by $\alpha _{p}=\sum _{i}g_{i}(p)(dh_{i})_{p}$ for each *p* ∈ *U*.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Any differential 1-form arises this way, and by using **(*)** it follows that any differential 1-form α on U may be expressed in coordinates as $\alpha =\sum _{i=1}^{n}f_{i}\,dx^{i}$ for some smooth functions *f**i* on U.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] The second idea leading to differential forms arises from the following question: given a differential 1-form α on U, when does there exist a function f on U such that *α* = *df*?
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] The above expansion reduces this question to the search for a function f whose partial derivatives ∂*f* / ∂*x**i* are equal to n given functions *f**i*.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] This is an example of a differential 2-form.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] This 2-form is called the exterior derivative *dα* of *α* = ∑*n* *j*=1 *f**j* *dx**j*.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] To summarize: *dα* = 0 is a necessary condition for the existence of a function f with *α* = *df*.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Differential 0-forms, 1-forms, and 2-forms are special cases of differential forms.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Antisymmetry, which was already present for 2-forms, makes it possible to restrict the sum to those sets of indices for which *i*1 < *i*2 < ... < *i**k*−1 < *i**k*.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Differential forms can be multiplied together using the exterior product, and for any differential k-form α, there is a differential (*k* + 1)-form *dα* called the exterior derivative of α.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Differential forms, the exterior product and the exterior derivative are independent of a choice of coordinates.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Consequently, they may be defined on any smooth manifold M.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] One way to do this is cover M with coordinate charts and define a differential k-form on M to be a family of differential k-forms on each chart which agree on the overlaps.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] However, there are more intrinsic definitions which make the independence of coordinates manifest.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] A smooth differential form of degree k is a smooth section of the k th exterior power of the cotangent bundle of M .
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] The set of all differential k -forms on a manifold M is a vector space, often denoted $\Omega ^{k}(M)$ .
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] The definition of a differential form may be restated as follows.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] At any point $p\in M$ , a k -form $\beta$ defines an element $\beta _{p}\in {\textstyle \bigwedge }^{k}T_{p}^{*}M,$ where $T_{p}M$ is the tangent space to M at p and $T_{p}^{*}(M)$ is its dual space.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] This space is naturally isomorphic to the fiber at p of the dual bundle of the k th exterior power of the tangent bundle of M .
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] By the universal property of exterior powers, this is equivalently an alternating multilinear map: $\beta _{p}\colon \bigoplus _{n=1}^{k}T_{p}M\to \mathbf {R} .$ Consequently, a differential k -form may be evaluated against any k -tuple of tangent vectors to the same point p of M .
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] For example, a differential 1 -form $\alpha$ assigns to each point $p\in M$ a linear functional $\alpha _{p}$ on $T_{p}M$ .
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] In the presence of an inner product on $T_{p}M$ (induced by a Riemannian metric on M ), $\alpha _{p}$ may be represented as the inner product with a tangent vector $X_{p}$ .
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Differential 1 -forms are sometimes called covariant vector fields, covector fields, or "dual vector fields", particularly within physics.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] The exterior algebra may be embedded in the tensor algebra by means of the alternation map.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] This map exhibits $\beta$ as a totally antisymmetric covariant tensor field of rank k .
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] The differential forms on M are in one-to-one correspondence with such tensor fields.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] As well as the addition and multiplication by scalar operations which arise from the vector space structure, there are several other standard operations defined on differential forms.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] The exterior product of a k -form $\alpha$ and an $\ell$ -form $\beta$ , denoted $\alpha \wedge \beta$ , is a $(k+\ell )$ -form.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] At each point p of the manifold M , the forms $\alpha$ and $\beta$ are elements of an exterior power of the cotangent space at p .
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] When the exterior algebra is viewed as a quotient of the tensor algebra, the exterior product corresponds to the tensor product (modulo the equivalence relation defining the exterior algebra).
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] The antisymmetry inherent in the exterior algebra means that when $\alpha \wedge \beta$ is viewed as a multilinear functional, it is alternating.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] However, when the exterior algebra is embedded as a subspace of the tensor algebra by means of the alternation map, the tensor product $\alpha \otimes \beta$ is not alternating.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] There is an explicit formula which describes the exterior product in this situation.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] For example, if $k=\ell =1$ , then $\alpha \wedge \beta$ is the 2 -form whose value at a point p is the alternating bilinear form defined by $(\alpha \wedge \beta )_{p}(v,w)=\alpha _{p}(v)\beta _{p}(w)-\alpha _{p}(w)\beta _{p}(v)$ for $v,w\in T_{p}M$ .
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] On a Riemannian manifold, or more generally a pseudo-Riemannian manifold, the metric defines a fibre-wise isomorphism of the tangent and cotangent bundles.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] This makes it possible to convert vector fields to covector fields and vice versa.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] On a pseudo-Riemannian manifold, 1-forms can be identified with vector fields; vector fields have additional distinct algebraic structures, which are listed here for context and to avoid confusion.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Firstly, each (co)tangent space generates a Clifford algebra, where the product of a (co)vector with itself is given by the value of a quadratic form – in this case, the natural one induced by the metric.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] This algebra is *distinct* from the exterior algebra of differential forms, which can be viewed as a Clifford algebra where the quadratic form vanishes (since the exterior product of any vector with itself is zero).
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Clifford algebras are thus non-anticommutative ("quantum") deformations of the exterior algebra.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Another alternative is to consider vector fields as derivations.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] The (noncommutative) algebra of differential operators they generate is the Weyl algebra and is a noncommutative ("quantum") deformation of the *symmetric* algebra in the vector fields.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] One important property of the exterior derivative is that $d^{2}=0$ .
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] This complex is called the de Rham complex, and its cohomology is by definition the de Rham cohomology of M .
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] By the Poincaré lemma, the de Rham complex is locally exact except at $\Omega ^{0}(M)$ .
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] The kernel at $\Omega ^{0}(M)$ is the space of locally constant functions on M .
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Therefore, the complex is a resolution of the constant sheaf ${\underline {\mathbf {R} }}$ , which in turn implies a form of de Rham's theorem: de Rham cohomology computes the sheaf cohomology of ${\underline {\mathbf {R} }}$ .
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] The differential of *f* is a smooth map *df* : *TM* → *TN* between the tangent bundles of *M* and *N*.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] This map is also denoted *f*∗ and called the **pushforward**.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] For any point *p* ∈ *M* and any tangent vector *v* ∈ *T**p**M*, there is a well-defined pushforward vector *f*∗(*v*) in *T**f*(*p*)*N*.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] However, the same is not true of a vector field.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] If *f* is not injective, say because *q* ∈ *N* has two or more preimages, then the vector field may determine two or more distinct vectors in *T**q**N*.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] If *f* is not surjective, then there will be a point *q* ∈ *N* at which *f*∗ does not determine any tangent vector at all.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Since a vector field on *N* determines, by definition, a unique tangent vector at every point of *N*, the pushforward of a vector field does not always exist.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] By contrast, it is always possible to pull back a differential form.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] A differential form on *N* may be viewed as a linear functional on each tangent space.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Precomposing this functional with the differential *df* : *TM* → *TN* defines a linear functional on each tangent space of *M* and therefore a differential form on *M*.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] The existence of pullbacks is one of the key features of the theory of differential forms.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] It leads to the existence of pullback maps in other situations, such as pullback homomorphisms in de Rham cohomology.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Formally, let *f* : *M* → *N* be smooth, and let *ω* be a smooth *k*-form on *N*.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Then there is a differential form *f*∗*ω* on *M*, called the **pullback** of *ω*, which captures the behavior of *ω* as seen relative to *f*.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] To define the pullback, fix a point *p* of *M* and tangent vectors *v*1, ..., *v**k* to *M* at *p*.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] There are several more abstract ways to view this definition.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] If *ω* is a 1-form on *N*, then it may be viewed as a section of the cotangent bundle *T*∗*N* of *N*.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Using ∗ to denote a dual map, the dual to the differential of *f* is (*df*)∗ : *T*∗*N* → *T*∗*M*.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] The pullback of *ω* may be defined to be the composite $M\ {\stackrel {f}{\to }}\ N\ {\stackrel {\omega }{\to }}\ T^{*}N\ {\stackrel {(df)^{*}}{\longrightarrow }}\ T^{*}M.$ This is a section of the cotangent bundle of *M* and hence a differential 1-form on *M*.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] In full generality, let ${\textstyle \bigwedge ^{k}(df)^{*}}$ denote the *k*th exterior power of the dual map to the differential.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Another abstract way to view the pullback comes from viewing a *k*-form *ω* as a linear functional on tangent spaces.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] From this point of view, *ω* is a morphism of vector bundles ${\textstyle \bigwedge }^{k}TN\ {\stackrel {\omega }{\to }}\ N\times \mathbf {R} ,$ where *N* × **R** is the trivial rank one bundle on *N*.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] The vector bundle morphism ${\textstyle {\textstyle \bigwedge }^{k}TM\to M\times \mathbf {R} }$ defined in this way is *f*∗*ω*.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Pullback respects all of the basic operations on forms.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] The pullback of a form can also be written in coordinates.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Assume that *x*1, ..., *x**m* are coordinates on *M*, that *y*1, ..., *y**n* are coordinates on *N*, and that these coordinate systems are related by the formulas *y**i* = *f**i*(*x*1, ..., *x**m*) for all *i*.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Each exterior derivative *df**i* can be expanded in terms of *dx*1, ..., *dx**m*.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] A differential *k*-form can be integrated over an oriented *k*-dimensional manifold.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] When the *k*-form is defined on an *n*-dimensional manifold with *n* > *k*, then the *k*-form can be integrated over oriented *k*-dimensional submanifolds.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] If *k* = 0, integration over oriented 0-dimensional submanifolds is just the summation of the integrand evaluated at points, according to the orientation of those points.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Other values of *k* = 1, 2, 3, ... correspond to line integrals, surface integrals, volume integrals, and so on.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] There are several equivalent ways to formally define the integral of a differential form, all of which depend on reducing to the case of Euclidean space.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Let U be an open subset of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Give $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ its standard orientation and U the restriction of that orientation.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Every smooth n -form $\omega$ on U has the form $\omega =f(x)\,dx^{1}\wedge \cdots \wedge dx^{n}$ for some smooth function $f:\mathbb {R} ^{n}\rightarrow \mathbb {R}$ .
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Such a function has an integral in the usual Riemann or Lebesgue sense.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] This allows us to define the integral of $\omega$ to be the integral of f : $\int _{U}\omega \ {\stackrel {\text{def}}{=}}\int _{U}f(x)\,dx^{1}\cdots dx^{n}.$ Fixing an orientation is necessary for this to be well-defined.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] The skew-symmetry of differential forms means that the integral of, say, ${\text{d}}x^{1}\wedge {\text{d}}x^{2}$ must be the negative of the integral of ${\text{d}}x^{2}\wedge {\text{d}}x^{1}$ .
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Riemann and Lebesgue integrals cannot see this dependence on the ordering of the coordinates, so they leave the sign of the integral undetermined.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] The orientation resolves this ambiguity.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Let M be an n -manifold and $\omega$ an n -form on M .
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] First, assume that there is a parametrization of M by an open subset of Euclidean space.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] That is, assume that there exists a diffeomorphism $\varphi \colon D\to M$ where $D\subseteq \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Give M the orientation induced by $\varphi$ .
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Then (Rudin 1976) defines the integral of $\omega$ over M to be the integral of $\varphi ^{*}\omega$ over D .
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] In coordinates, this has the following expression.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Fix an embedding of M in $\mathbb {R} ^{I}$ with coordinates $x^{1},\ldots ,x^{I}$ .
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] The Jacobian exists because $\varphi$ is differentiable.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] In general, an n -manifold cannot be parametrized by an open subset of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] But such a parametrization is always possible locally, so it is possible to define integrals over arbitrary manifolds by defining them as sums of integrals over collections of local parametrizations.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Moreover, it is also possible to define parametrizations of k -dimensional subsets for $k<n$ , and this makes it possible to define integrals of k -forms.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] To make this precise, it is convenient to fix a standard domain D in $\mathbb {R} ^{k}$ , usually a cube or a simplex.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] A k -**chain** is a formal sum of smooth embeddings $D\rightarrow M$ .
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] That is, it is a collection of smooth embeddings, each of which is assigned an integer multiplicity.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Each smooth embedding determines a k -dimensional submanifold of M .
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] This approach to defining integration does not assign a direct meaning to integration over the whole manifold M .
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] However, it is still possible to assign such a meaning indirectly because every smooth manifold may be smoothly triangulated in an essentially unique way, and the integral over M may be defined to be the integral over the chain determined by a triangulation.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] There is another approach, expounded in (Dieudonné 1972), which does directly assign a meaning to integration over M , but this approach requires fixing an orientation of M .
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] The integral of an n -form $\omega$ on an n -dimensional manifold is defined by working in charts.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Suppose first that $\omega$ is supported on a single positively oriented chart.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] On this chart, it may be pulled back to an n -form on an open subset of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Here, the form has a well-defined Riemann or Lebesgue integral as before.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] The change of variables formula and the assumption that the chart is positively oriented together ensure that the integral of $\omega$ is independent of the chosen chart.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] In the general case, use a partition of unity to write $\omega$ as a sum of n -forms, each of which is supported in a single positively oriented chart, and define the integral of $\omega$ to be the sum of the integrals of each term in the partition of unity.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] It is also possible to integrate k -forms on oriented k -dimensional submanifolds using this more intrinsic approach.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] The form is pulled back to the submanifold, where the integral is defined using charts as before.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] For example, given a path $\gamma (t):[0,1]\rightarrow \mathbb {R} ^{2}$ , integrating a 1 -form on the path is simply pulling back the form to a form $f(t){\text{d}}t$ on $[0,1]$ , and this integral is the integral of the function $f(t)$ on the interval.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Fubini's theorem states that the integral over a set that is a product may be computed as an iterated integral over the two factors in the product.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] This suggests that the integral of a differential form over a product ought to be computable as an iterated integral as well.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] The geometric flexibility of differential forms ensures that this is possible not just for products, but in more general situations as well.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Under some hypotheses, it is possible to integrate along the fibers of a smooth map, and the analog of Fubini's theorem is the case where this map is the projection from a product to one of its factors.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Because integrating a differential form over a submanifold requires fixing an orientation, a prerequisite to integration along fibers is the existence of a well-defined orientation on those fibers.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Let *M* and *N* be two orientable manifolds of pure dimensions *m* and *n*, respectively.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Suppose that *f* : *M* → *N* is a surjective submersion.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] This implies that each fiber *f*−1(*y*) is (*m* − *n*)-dimensional and that, around each point of *M*, there is a chart on which *f* looks like the projection from a product onto one of its factors.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Following (Dieudonné 1972), there is a unique $\sigma _{x}\in {\textstyle \bigwedge }^{m-n}T_{x}^{*}(f^{-1}(y))$ which may be thought of as the fibral part of *ω**x* with respect to *η**y*.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] More precisely, define *j* : *f*−1(*y*) → *M* to be the inclusion.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Moreover, for fixed *y*, *σ**x* varies smoothly with respect to *x*.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] That is, suppose that $\omega \colon f^{-1}(y)\to T^{*}M$ is a smooth section of the projection map; we say that *ω* is a smooth differential *m*-form on *M* along *f*−1(*y*).
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] The same construction works if *ω* is an *m*-form in a neighborhood of the fiber, and the same notation is used.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] A consequence is that each fiber *f*−1(*y*) is orientable.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] In particular, a choice of orientation forms on *M* and *N* defines an orientation of every fiber of *f*.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] The analog of Fubini's theorem is as follows.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] As before, *M* and *N* are two orientable manifolds of pure dimensions *m* and *n*, and *f* : *M* → *N* is a surjective submersion.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Fix orientations of *M* and *N*, and give each fiber of *f* the induced orientation.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Let *ω* be an *m*-form on *M*, and let *η* be an *n*-form on *N* that is almost everywhere positive with respect to the orientation of *N*.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Then, for almost every *y* ∈ *N*, the form *ω* / *η**y* is a well-defined integrable *m* − *n* form on *f*−1(*y*).
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] It is also possible to integrate forms of other degrees along the fibers of a submersion.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Assume the same hypotheses as before, and let *α* be a compactly supported (*m* − *n* + *k*)-form on *M*.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Then there is a *k*-form *γ* on *N* which is the result of integrating *α* along the fibers of *f*.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] The form *α* is defined by specifying, at each *y* ∈ *N*, how *γ* pairs with each *k*-vector **v** at *y*, and the value of that pairing is an integral over *f*−1(*y*) that depends only on *α*, **v**, and the orientations of *M* and *N*.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] More precisely, at each *y* ∈ *N*, there is an isomorphism ${\textstyle \bigwedge }^{k}T_{y}N\to {\textstyle \bigwedge }^{n-k}T_{y}^{*}N$ defined by the interior product $\mathbf {v} \mapsto \mathbf {v} \,\lrcorner \,\zeta _{y},$ for any choice of volume form *ζ* in the orientation of *N*.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Then the *k*-form *γ* is uniquely defined by the property $\langle \gamma _{y},\mathbf {v} \rangle =\int _{f^{-1}(y)}\beta _{\mathbf {v} },$ and *γ* is smooth (Dieudonné 1972).
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] This form also denoted *α*♭ and called the **integral of *α* along the fibers of *f***.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Integration along fibers is important for the construction of Gysin maps in de Rham cohomology.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Integration along fibers satisfies the **projection formula** (Dieudonné 1972).
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] This case is called the gradient theorem, and generalizes the fundamental theorem of calculus.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] This path independence is very useful in contour integration.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] This theorem also underlies the duality between de Rham cohomology and the homology of chains.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] The simplest example is attempting to integrate the 1-form *dx* over the interval [0, 1].
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Assuming the usual distance (and thus measure) on the real line, this integral is either 1 or −1, depending on *orientation*: ${\textstyle \int _{0}^{1}dx=1}$ , while ${\textstyle \int _{1}^{0}dx=-\int _{0}^{1}dx=-1}$ .
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] By contrast, the integral of the *measure* |*dx*| on the interval is unambiguously 1 (i.e. the integral of the constant function 1 with respect to this measure is 1).
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Similarly, under a change of coordinates a differential *n*-form changes by the Jacobian determinant *J*, while a measure changes by the *absolute value* of the Jacobian determinant, |*J*|, which further reflects the issue of orientation.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] For example, under the map *x* ↦ −*x* on the line, the differential form *dx* pulls back to −*dx*; orientation has reversed; while the Lebesgue measure, which here we denote |*dx*|, pulls back to |*dx*|; it does not change.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] In the presence of the additional data of an *orientation*, it is possible to integrate *n*-forms (top-dimensional forms) over the entire manifold or over compact subsets; integration over the entire manifold corresponds to integrating the form over the fundamental class of the manifold, [*M*].
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Formally, in the presence of an orientation, one may identify *n*-forms with densities on a manifold; densities in turn define a measure, and thus can be integrated (Folland 1999, Section 11.4, pp.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] On an orientable but not oriented manifold, there are two choices of orientation; either choice allows one to integrate *n*-forms over compact subsets, with the two choices differing by a sign.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] One can instead identify densities with top-dimensional pseudoforms.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Even in the presence of an orientation, there is in general no meaningful way to integrate *k*-forms over subsets for *k* < *n* because there is no consistent way to use the ambient orientation to orient *k*-dimensional subsets.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Geometrically, a *k*-dimensional subset can be turned around in place, yielding the same subset with the opposite orientation; for example, the horizontal axis in a plane can be rotated by 180 degrees.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Compare the Gram determinant of a set of *k* vectors in an *n*-dimensional space, which, unlike the determinant of *n* vectors, is always positive, corresponding to a squared number.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] An orientation of a *k*-submanifold is therefore extra data not derivable from the ambient manifold.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] On a Riemannian manifold, one may define a *k*-dimensional Hausdorff measure for any *k* (integer or real), which may be integrated over *k*-dimensional subsets of the manifold.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] A function times this Hausdorff measure can then be integrated over *k*-dimensional subsets, providing a measure-theoretic analog to integration of *k*-forms.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] The *n*-dimensional Hausdorff measure yields a density, as above.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] The differential form analog of a distribution or generalized function is called a **current**.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] The space of *k*-currents on *M* is the dual space to an appropriate space of differential *k*-forms.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p01] Currents play the role of generalized domains of integration, similar to but even more flexible than chains.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p02] Differential forms arise in some important physical contexts.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p02] This form is a special case of the curvature form on the U(1) principal bundle on which both electromagnetism and general gauge theories may be described.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p02] The connection form for the principal bundle is the vector potential, typically denoted by $\mathbf {A}$ , when represented in some gauge.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p02] (Here it is a matter of convention to write $F_{ab}$ instead of $f_{ab}$ , i.e. to use capital letters, and to write $J^{a}$ instead of $j_{a}$ .
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p02] However, the vector rsp. tensor components and the above-mentioned forms have different physical dimensions.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p02] Using the above-mentioned definitions, Maxwell's equations can be written very compactly in geometrized units as ${\begin{aligned}d{\mathbf {F} }&=\mathbf {0} \\d{\star \mathbf {F} }&=\mathbf {J} ,\end{aligned}}$ where $\star$ denotes the Hodge star operator.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p02] Similar considerations describe the geometry of gauge theories in general.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p02] The 2 -form ${\star }\mathbf {F}$ , which is dual to the Faraday form, is also called **Maxwell 2-form**.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p02] Electromagnetism is an example of a U(1) gauge theory.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p02] Here the Lie group is ${\text{U}}(1)$ , the one-dimensional unitary group, which is in particular abelian.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p02] There are gauge theories, such as Yang–Mills theory, in which the Lie group is not abelian.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p02] In that case, one gets relations which are similar to those described here.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p02] The analog of the field $\mathbf {F}$ in such theories is the curvature form of the connection, which is represented in a gauge by a Lie algebra-valued one-form $\mathbf {A}$ .
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p02] In the abelian case, such as electromagnetism, $\mathbf {A} \wedge \mathbf {A} =0$ , but this does not hold in general.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p02] Likewise the field equations are modified by additional terms involving exterior products of $\mathbf {A}$ and $\mathbf {F}$ , owing to the structure equations of the gauge group.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p02] Numerous minimality results for complex analytic manifolds are based on the Wirtinger inequality for 2-forms.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p02] A succinct proof may be found in Herbert Federer's classic text *Geometric Measure Theory*.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-form-p02] The Wirtinger inequality is also a key ingredient in Gromov's inequality for complex projective space in systolic geometry.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Since the late 19th century, differential geometry has grown into a field concerned more generally with geometric structures on differentiable manifolds.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] A geometric structure is one which defines some notion of size, distance, shape, volume, or other rigidifying structure.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] For example, in Riemannian geometry distances and angles are specified, in symplectic geometry volumes may be computed, in conformal geometry only angles are specified, and in gauge theory certain fields are given over the space.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Differential geometry is also related to the geometric aspects of the theory of differential equations, otherwise known as geometric analysis.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Differential geometry finds applications throughout mathematics and the natural sciences.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Most prominently the language of differential geometry was used by Albert Einstein in his general theory of relativity, and subsequently by physicists in the development of quantum field theory and the Standard Model of particle physics.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Outside of physics, differential geometry finds applications in chemistry, economics, engineering, control theory, computer graphics and computer vision, and recently in machine learning.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] The history and development of differential geometry as a subject begins at least as far back as classical antiquity.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] It is intimately linked to the development of geometry more generally, of the notion of space and shape, and of topology, especially the study of manifolds.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] In this section we focus primarily on the history of the application of infinitesimal methods to geometry, and later to the ideas of tangent spaces, and eventually the development of the modern formalism of the subject in terms of tensors and tensor fields.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] The study of differential geometry, or at least the study of the geometry of smooth shapes, can be traced back at least to classical antiquity.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] In particular, much was known about the geometry of the Earth, a spherical geometry, in the time of the ancient Greek mathematicians.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Famously, Eratosthenes calculated the circumference of the Earth around 200 BC, and around 150 AD Ptolemy in his *Geography* introduced the stereographic projection for the purposes of mapping the shape of the Earth.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Implicitly throughout this time principles that form the foundation of differential geometry and calculus were used in geodesy, although in a much simplified form.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Indeed, the measurements of distance along such geodesic paths by Eratosthenes and others can be considered a rudimentary measure of arclength of curves, a concept which did not see a rigorous definition in terms of calculus until the 1600s.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Around this time there were only minimal overt applications of the theory of infinitesimals to the study of geometry, a precursor to the modern calculus-based study of the subject.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] In Euclid's *Elements* the notion of tangency of a line to a circle is discussed, and Archimedes applied the method of exhaustion to compute the areas of smooth shapes such as the circle, and the volumes of smooth three-dimensional solids such as the sphere, cones, and cylinders.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] There was little development in the theory of differential geometry between antiquity and the beginning of the Renaissance.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Before the development of calculus by Newton and Leibniz, the most significant development in the understanding of differential geometry came from Gerardus Mercator's development of the Mercator projection as a way of mapping the Earth.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Mercator had an understanding of the advantages and pitfalls of his map design, and in particular was aware of the conformal nature of his projection, as well as the difference between *praga*, the lines of shortest distance on the Earth, and the *directio*, the straight line paths on his map.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Mercator noted that the praga were *oblique curvatur* in this projection.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] This fact reflects the lack of a metric-preserving map of the Earth's surface onto a flat plane, a consequence of the later Theorema Egregium of Gauss.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] The first systematic or rigorous treatment of geometry using the theory of infinitesimals and notions from calculus began around the 1600s when calculus was first developed by Gottfried Leibniz and Isaac Newton.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] At this time, the recent work of René Descartes introducing analytic coordinates to geometry allowed geometric shapes of increasing complexity to be described rigorously.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] In particular around this time Pierre de Fermat, Newton, and Leibniz began the study of plane curves and the investigation of concepts such as points of inflection and circles of osculation, which aid in the measurement of curvature.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Indeed, already in his first paper on the foundations of calculus, Leibniz notes that the infinitesimal condition $d^{2}y=0$ indicates the existence of an inflection point.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Shortly after this time the Bernoulli brothers, Jacob and Johann made important early contributions to the use of infinitesimals to study geometry.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] In lectures by Johann Bernoulli at the time, later collated by L'Hopital into the first textbook on differential calculus, the tangents to plane curves of various types are computed using the condition $dy=0$ , and similarly points of inflection are calculated.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] At this same time the orthogonality between the osculating circles of a plane curve and the tangent directions is realised, and the first analytical formula for the radius of an osculating circle, essentially the first analytical formula for the notion of curvature, is written down.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] In the wake of the development of analytic geometry and plane curves, Alexis Clairaut began the study of space curves at just the age of 16.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] In his book Clairaut introduced the notion of tangent and subtangent directions to space curves in relation to the directions which lie along a surface on which the space curve lies.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Thus Clairaut demonstrated an implicit understanding of the tangent space of a surface and studied this idea using calculus for the first time.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Importantly Clairaut introduced the terminology of *curvature* and *double curvature*, essentially the notion of principal curvatures later studied by Gauss and others.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Around this same time, Leonhard Euler, originally a student of Johann Bernoulli, provided many significant contributions not just to the development of geometry, but to mathematics more broadly.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] This theory was used by Lagrange, a co-developer of the calculus of variations, to derive the first differential equation describing a minimal surface in terms of the Euler–Lagrange equation.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] In 1760 Euler proved a theorem expressing the curvature of a space curve on a surface in terms of the principal curvatures, known as Euler's theorem.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Later in the 1700s, the new French school led by Gaspard Monge began to make contributions to differential geometry.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Monge made important contributions to the theory of plane curves, surfaces, and studied surfaces of revolution and envelopes of plane curves and space curves.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Several students of Monge made contributions to this same theory, and for example Charles Dupin provided a new interpretation of Euler's theorem in terms of the principle curvatures, which is the modern form of the equation.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Dubbed the single most important work in the history of differential geometry, in 1827 Gauss produced the *Disquisitiones generales circa superficies curvas* detailing the general theory of curved surfaces.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] In this work and his subsequent papers and unpublished notes on the theory of surfaces, Gauss has been dubbed the inventor of non-Euclidean geometry and the inventor of intrinsic differential geometry.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] At this time Gauss was already of the opinion that the standard paradigm of Euclidean geometry should be discarded, and was in possession of private manuscripts on non-Euclidean geometry which informed his study of geodesic triangles.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Around this same time János Bolyai and Lobachevsky independently discovered hyperbolic geometry and thus demonstrated the existence of consistent geometries outside Euclid's paradigm.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Concrete models of hyperbolic geometry were produced by Eugenio Beltrami later in the 1860s, and Felix Klein coined the term non-Euclidean geometry in 1871, and through the Erlangen program put Euclidean and non-Euclidean geometries on the same footing.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Implicitly, the spherical geometry of the Earth that had been studied since antiquity was a non-Euclidean geometry, an elliptic geometry.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] The development of intrinsic differential geometry in the language of Gauss was spurred on by his student, Bernhard Riemann in his Habilitationsschrift, *On the hypotheses which lie at the foundation of geometry*.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] In this work Riemann introduced the notion of a Riemannian metric and the Riemannian curvature tensor for the first time, and began the systematic study of differential geometry in higher dimensions.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] This intrinsic point of view in terms of the Riemannian metric, denoted by $ds^{2}$ by Riemann, was the development of an idea of Gauss's about the linear element $ds$ of a surface.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] At this time Riemann began to introduce the systematic use of linear algebra and multilinear algebra into the subject, making great use of the theory of quadratic forms in his investigation of metrics and curvature.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] The notion of groups of transformations was developed by Sophus Lie and Jean Gaston Darboux, leading to important results in the theory of Lie groups and symplectic geometry.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] The notion of differential calculus on curved spaces was studied by Elwin Christoffel, who introduced the Christoffel symbols which describe the covariant derivative in 1868, and by others including Eugenio Beltrami who studied many analytic questions on manifolds.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] It was in this language that differential geometry was used by Einstein in the development of general relativity and pseudo-Riemannian geometry.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] The subject of modern differential geometry emerged from the early 1900s in response to the foundational contributions of many mathematicians, including importantly the work of Henri Poincaré on the foundations of topology.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] At the start of the 1900s there was a major movement within mathematics to formalise the foundational aspects of the subject to avoid crises of rigour and accuracy, known as Hilbert's program.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] As part of this broader movement, the notion of a topological space was distilled in by Felix Hausdorff in 1914, and by 1942 there were many different notions of manifold of a combinatorial and differential-geometric nature.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Interest in the subject was also focused by the emergence of Einstein's theory of general relativity and the importance of the Einstein Field equations.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Of particular importance was Hermann Weyl who made important contributions to the foundations of general relativity, introduced the Weyl tensor providing insight into conformal geometry, and first defined the notion of a gauge leading to the development of gauge theory in physics and mathematics.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] In the middle and late 20th century differential geometry as a subject expanded in scope and developed links to other areas of mathematics and physics.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] The development of gauge theory and Yang–Mills theory in physics brought bundles and connections into focus, leading to developments in gauge theory.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Many analytical results were investigated including the proof of the Atiyah–Singer index theorem.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] The development of complex geometry was spurred on by parallel results in algebraic geometry, and results in the geometry and global analysis of complex manifolds were proven by Shing-Tung Yau and others.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] In the latter half of the 20th century new analytic techniques were developed in regards to curvature flows such as the Ricci flow, which culminated in Grigori Perelman's proof of the Poincaré conjecture.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] During this same period primarily due to the influence of Michael Atiyah, new links between theoretical physics and differential geometry were formed.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Techniques from the study of the Yang–Mills equations and gauge theory were used by mathematicians to develop new invariants of smooth manifolds.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Riemannian geometry studies Riemannian manifolds, smooth manifolds with a *Riemannian metric*.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] This is a concept of distance expressed by means of a smooth positive definite symmetric bilinear form defined on the tangent space at each point.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Riemannian geometry generalizes Euclidean geometry to spaces that are not necessarily flat, though they still resemble Euclidean space at each point infinitesimally, i.e. in the first order of approximation.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Various concepts based on length, such as the arc length of curves, area of plane regions, and volume of solids all possess natural analogues in Riemannian geometry.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] The notion of a directional derivative of a function from multivariable calculus is extended to the notion of a covariant derivative of a tensor.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Many concepts of analysis and differential equations have been generalized to the setting of Riemannian manifolds.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] A distance-preserving diffeomorphism between Riemannian manifolds is called an isometry.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] This notion can also be defined *locally*, i.e. for small neighborhoods of points.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Any two regular curves are locally isometric.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] However, the Theorema Egregium of Carl Friedrich Gauss showed that for surfaces, the existence of a local isometry imposes that the Gaussian curvatures at the corresponding points must be the same.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] In higher dimensions, the Riemann curvature tensor is an important pointwise invariant associated with a Riemannian manifold that measures how close it is to being flat.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] An important class of Riemannian manifolds is the Riemannian symmetric spaces, whose curvature is not necessarily constant.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] These are the closest analogues to the "ordinary" plane and space considered in Euclidean and non-Euclidean geometry.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Pseudo-Riemannian geometry generalizes Riemannian geometry to the case in which the metric tensor need not be positive-definite.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] A special case of this is a Lorentzian manifold, which is the mathematical basis of Einstein's general relativity theory of gravity.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Finsler geometry has *Finsler manifolds* as the main object of study.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] This is a differential manifold with a *Finsler metric*, that is, a Banach norm defined on each tangent space.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Riemannian manifolds are special cases of the more general Finsler manifolds.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] The vertical Hessian of $F^{2}$ is positive definite.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Symplectic geometry is the study of symplectic manifolds.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] An **almost symplectic manifold** is a differentiable manifold equipped with a smoothly varying non-degenerate skew-symmetric bilinear form on each tangent space, i.e., a nondegenerate 2-form *ω*, called the *symplectic form*.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] A symplectic manifold is an almost symplectic manifold for which the symplectic form *ω* is closed: d*ω* = 0.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] A diffeomorphism between two symplectic manifolds which preserves the symplectic form is called a symplectomorphism.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Non-degenerate skew-symmetric bilinear forms can only exist on even-dimensional vector spaces, so symplectic manifolds necessarily have even dimension.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] In dimension 2, a symplectic manifold is just a surface endowed with an area form and a symplectomorphism is an area-preserving diffeomorphism.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] The phase space of a mechanical system is a symplectic manifold and they made an implicit appearance already in the work of Joseph Louis Lagrange on analytical mechanics and later in Carl Gustav Jacobi's and William Rowan Hamilton's formulations of classical mechanics.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] By contrast with Riemannian geometry, where the curvature provides a local invariant of Riemannian manifolds, Darboux's theorem states that all symplectic manifolds are locally isomorphic.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] The only invariants of a symplectic manifold are global in nature and topological aspects play a prominent role in symplectic geometry.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] The first result in symplectic topology is probably the Poincaré–Birkhoff theorem, conjectured by Henri Poincaré and then proved by G.D.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] It claims that if an area preserving map of an annulus twists each boundary component in opposite directions, then the map has at least two fixed points.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Contact geometry deals with certain manifolds of odd dimension.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] It is close to symplectic geometry and like the latter, it originated in questions of classical mechanics.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] A local 1-form on *M* is a *contact form* if the restriction of its exterior derivative to *H* is a non-degenerate two-form and thus induces a symplectic structure on *H**p* at each point.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] is a volume form on *M*, i.e. does not vanish anywhere.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] A contact analogue of the Darboux theorem holds: all contact structures on an odd-dimensional manifold are locally isomorphic and can be brought to a certain local normal form by a suitable choice of the coordinate system.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] It follows from this definition that an almost complex manifold is even-dimensional.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] An almost complex manifold is called *complex* if $N_{J}=0$ , where $N_{J}$ is a tensor of type (2, 1) related to J , called the Nijenhuis tensor (or sometimes the *torsion*).
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] An almost complex manifold is complex if and only if it admits a holomorphic coordinate atlas.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] where $\nabla$ is the Levi-Civita connection of g .
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] In this case, $(J,g)$ is called a *Kähler structure*, and a *Kähler manifold* is a manifold endowed with a Kähler structure.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] In particular, a Kähler manifold is both a complex and a symplectic manifold.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] A large class of Kähler manifolds (the class of Hodge manifolds) is given by all the smooth complex projective varieties.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] CR geometry is the study of the intrinsic geometry of boundaries of domains in complex manifolds.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Conformal geometry is the study of the set of angle-preserving (conformal) transformations on a space.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Differential topology is the study of global geometric invariants without a metric or symplectic form.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Differential topology starts from the natural operations such as Lie derivative of natural vector bundles and de Rham differential of forms.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Beside Lie algebroids, also Courant algebroids start playing a more important role.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] A Lie group is a group in the category of smooth manifolds.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Beside the algebraic properties this enjoys also differential geometric properties.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] The most obvious construction is that of a Lie algebra which is the tangent space at the unit endowed with the Lie bracket between left-invariant vector fields.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Beside the structure theory there is also the wide field of representation theory.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Geometric analysis is a mathematical discipline where tools from differential equations, especially elliptic partial differential equations are used to establish new results in differential geometry and differential topology.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Gauge theory is the study of connections on vector bundles and principal bundles, and arises out of problems in mathematical physics and physical gauge theories which underpin the Standard Model of particle physics.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Gauge theory is concerned with the study of differential equations for connections on bundles, and the resulting geometric moduli spaces of solutions to these equations as well as the invariants that may be derived from them.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] These equations often arise as the Euler–Lagrange equations describing the equations of motion of certain physical systems in quantum field theory, and so their study is of considerable interest in physics.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] The apparatus of vector bundles, principal bundles, and connections on bundles plays an extraordinarily important role in modern differential geometry.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] A smooth manifold always carries a natural vector bundle, the tangent bundle.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Loosely speaking, this structure by itself is sufficient only for developing analysis on the manifold, while doing geometry requires, in addition, some way to relate the tangent spaces at different points, i.e. a notion of parallel transport.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] An important example is provided by affine connections.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] For a surface in **R**3, tangent planes at different points can be identified using a natural path-wise parallelism induced by the ambient Euclidean space, which has a well-known standard definition of metric and parallelism.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] In Riemannian geometry, the Levi-Civita connection serves a similar purpose.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] More generally, differential geometers consider spaces with a vector bundle and an arbitrary affine connection which is not defined in terms of a metric.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] In physics, the manifold may be spacetime and the bundles and connections are related to various physical fields.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] From the beginning and through the middle of the 19th century, differential geometry was studied from the *extrinsic* point of view: curves and surfaces were considered as lying in a Euclidean space of higher dimension (for example a surface in an ambient space of three dimensions).
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] The simplest results are those in the differential geometry of curves and differential geometry of surfaces.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Starting with the work of Riemann, the *intrinsic* point of view was developed, in which one cannot speak of moving "outside" the geometric object because it is considered to be given in a free-standing way.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] The fundamental result here is Gauss's theorema egregium, to the effect that Gaussian curvature is an intrinsic invariant.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] The intrinsic point of view is more flexible.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] For example, it is useful in relativity where space-time cannot naturally be taken as extrinsic.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] However, there is a price to pay in technical complexity: the intrinsic definitions of curvature and connections become much less visually intuitive.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] These two points of view can be reconciled, i.e. the extrinsic geometry can be considered as a structure additional to the intrinsic one.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] (See the Nash embedding theorem.) In the formalism of geometric calculus both extrinsic and intrinsic geometry of a manifold can be characterized by a single bivector-valued one-form called the shape operator.
[src:differential-geometry/differential-geometry] Below are some examples of how differential geometry is applied to other fields of science and mathematics.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] In geometry, a **geodesic** (/ˌdʒiː.əˈdɛsɪk, -oʊ-, -ˈdiːsɪk, -zɪk/) is a curve representing in some sense the locally shortest path (arc) between two points in a surface, or more generally in a Riemannian manifold.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] The term also has meaning in any differentiable manifold with a connection.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] It is a generalization of the notion of a "straight line".
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] The noun *geodesic* and the adjective *geodetic* come from *geodesy*, the science of measuring the size and shape of Earth, though many of the underlying principles can be applied to any ellipsoidal geometry.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] In the original sense, a geodesic was the shortest route between two points on the Earth's surface.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] For a spherical Earth, it is a segment of a great circle (see also great-circle distance).
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] The term has since been generalized to more abstract mathematical spaces; for example, in graph theory, one might consider a geodesic between two vertices/nodes of a graph.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] In a Riemannian manifold or submanifold, geodesics are characterised by the property of having vanishing geodesic curvature.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] More generally, in the presence of an affine connection, a geodesic is defined to be a curve whose tangent vectors remain parallel if they are transported along it.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] Applying this to the Levi-Civita connection of a Riemannian metric recovers the previous notion.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] Geodesics are of particular importance in general relativity.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] Timelike geodesics in general relativity describe the motion of free falling test particles.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] This has some minor technical problems because there is an infinite-dimensional space of different ways to parameterize the shortest path.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] It is simpler to restrict the set of curves to those that are parameterized "with constant speed" 1, meaning that the distance from *f*(*s*) to *f*(*t*) along the curve equals |*s*−*t*|.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] Equivalently, a different quantity may be used, termed the energy of the curve; minimizing the energy leads to the same equations for a geodesic (here "constant velocity" is a consequence of minimization).
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] Intuitively, one can understand this second formulation by noting that an elastic band stretched between two points will contract its width, and in so doing will minimize its energy.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] The resulting shape of the band is a geodesic.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] It is possible that several different curves between two points minimize the distance, as is the case for two diametrically opposite points on a sphere.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] In such a case, any of these curves is a geodesic.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] A contiguous segment of a geodesic is again a geodesic.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] In general, geodesics are not the same as "shortest curves" between two points, though the two concepts are closely related.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] The difference is that geodesics are only *locally* the shortest distance between points, and are parameterized with "constant speed".
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] Going the "long way round" on a great circle between two points on a sphere is a geodesic but not the shortest path between the points.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] The map $t\to t^{2}$ from the unit interval on the real number line to itself gives the shortest path between 0 and 1, but is not a geodesic because the velocity of the corresponding motion of a point is not constant.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] Geodesics are commonly seen in the study of Riemannian geometry and more generally metric geometry.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] In general relativity, geodesics in spacetime describe the motion of point particles under the influence of gravity alone.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] In particular, the path taken by a falling rock, an orbiting satellite, or the shape of a planetary orbit are all geodesics in curved spacetime.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] More generally, the topic of sub-Riemannian geometry deals with the paths that objects may take when they are not free, and their movement is constrained in various ways.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] This article presents the mathematical formalism involved in defining, finding, and proving the existence of geodesics, in the case of Riemannian manifolds.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] The article Levi-Civita connection discusses the more general case of a pseudo-Riemannian manifold and geodesic (general relativity) discusses the special case of general relativity in greater detail.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] The most familiar examples are the straight lines in Euclidean geometry.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] On a sphere, the images of geodesics are the great circles.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] The shortest path from point *A* to point *B* on a sphere is given by the shorter arc of the great circle passing through *A* and *B*.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] If *A* and *B* are antipodal points, then there are *infinitely many* shortest paths between them.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] Geodesics on an ellipsoid behave in a more complicated way than on a sphere; in particular, they are not closed in general (see figure).
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] A **geodesic triangle** is formed by the geodesics joining each pair out of three points on a given surface.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] On the sphere, the geodesics are great circle arcs, forming a spherical triangle.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] In metric geometry, a geodesic is a curve which is everywhere locally a distance minimizer.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] This generalizes the notion of geodesic for Riemannian manifolds.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] If the last equality is satisfied for all *t*1, *t*2 ∈ *I*, the geodesic is called a **minimizing geodesic** or **shortest path**.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] In general, a metric space may have no geodesics, except constant curves.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] At the other extreme, any two points in a length metric space are joined by a minimizing sequence of rectifiable paths, although this minimizing sequence need not converge to a geodesic.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] The metric Hopf-Rinow theorem provides situations where a length space is automatically a geodesic space.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] Common examples of geodesic metric spaces that are often not manifolds include metric graphs, (locally compact) metric polyhedral complexes, infinite-dimensional pre-Hilbert spaces, and real trees.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] The distance $d(p,q)$ between two points p and q of M is defined as the infimum of the length taken over all continuous, piecewise continuously differentiable curves $\gamma :[a,b]\to M$ such that $\gamma (a)=p$ and $\gamma (b)=q$ .
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] In Riemannian geometry, all geodesics are locally distance-minimizing paths, but the converse is not true.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] In fact, only paths that are both locally distance minimizing and parameterized proportionately to arc-length are geodesics.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] All minima of E are also minima of L , but L is a bigger set since paths that are minima of L can be arbitrarily re-parameterized (without changing their length), while minima of E cannot.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] with equality if and only if $g(\gamma ',\gamma ')$ is equal to a constant a.e.; the path should be travelled at constant speed.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] It happens that minimizers of $E(\gamma )$ also minimize $L(\gamma )$ , because they turn out to be affinely parameterized, and the inequality is an equality.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] The usefulness of this approach is that the problem of seeking minimizers of E is a more robust variational problem.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] Indeed, $E(\gamma )$ is a "convex function" of $\gamma$ , so that within each isotopy class of "reasonable functions", one ought to expect existence, uniqueness, and regularity of minimizers.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] In contrast, "minimizers" of the functional $L(\gamma )$ are generally not very regular, because arbitrary reparameterizations are allowed.
