[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] Thus apart from specifying a certain class of embedded curves, the geodesic equation also determines a preferred class of parameterizations on each of the curves.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] Accordingly, solutions of (**1**) are called geodesics with **affine parameter**.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] An affine connection is *determined by* its family of affinely parameterized geodesics, up to torsion (Spivak 1999, Chapter 6, Addendum I).
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] The torsion itself does not, in fact, affect the family of geodesics, since the geodesic equation depends only on the symmetric part of the connection.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] is skew-symmetric, then $\nabla$ and ${\bar {\nabla }}$ have the same geodesics, with the same affine parameterizations.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] Furthermore, there is a unique connection having the same geodesics as $\nabla$ , but with vanishing torsion.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] Geodesics without a particular parameterization are described by a projective connection.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] Efficient solvers for the minimal geodesic problem on surfaces have been proposed by Mitchell, Kimmel, Crane, and others.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] A ribbon "test" is a way of finding a geodesic on a physical surface.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] The idea is to fit a bit of paper around a straight line (a ribbon) onto a curved surface as closely as possible without stretching or squishing the ribbon (without changing its internal geometry).
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] For example, when a ribbon is wound as a ring around a cone, the ribbon would not lie on the cone's surface but stick out, so that circle is not a geodesic on the cone.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] If the ribbon is adjusted so that all its parts touch the cone's surface, it would give an approximation to a geodesic.
[src:differential-geometry/geodesic] While geometric in nature, the idea of a shortest path is so general that it easily finds extensive use in nearly all sciences, and in some other disciplines as well.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] In differential geometry, a **Riemannian manifold** (or **Riemann space**) is a geometric space on which many geometric notions such as distance, angles, length, volume, and curvature are defined.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Euclidean space, the n -sphere, hyperbolic space, and smooth surfaces in three-dimensional space, such as ellipsoids and paraboloids, are all examples of Riemannian manifolds.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Riemannian manifolds take their name from German mathematician Bernhard Riemann, who first conceptualized them in 1854.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Formally, a **Riemannian metric** (or just a **metric**) on a smooth manifold is a smoothly varying choice of inner product for each tangent space of the manifold.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] A Riemannian manifold is a smooth manifold together with a Riemannian metric.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] The techniques of differential and integral calculus are used to pull geometric data out of the Riemannian metric.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] For example, integration leads to the Riemannian distance function, whereas differentiation is used to define curvature and parallel transport.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Any smooth surface in three-dimensional Euclidean space is a Riemannian manifold with a Riemannian metric coming from the way it sits inside the ambient space.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] The same is true for any submanifold of Euclidean space of any dimension.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] In many instances, such as for hyperbolic space and projective space, Riemannian metrics are more naturally defined or constructed using the intrinsic point of view.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Riemannian geometry, the study of Riemannian manifolds, has deep connections to other areas of mathematics, including geometric topology, complex geometry, and algebraic geometry.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Applications include physics (especially general relativity and gauge theory), computer graphics, machine learning, and cartography.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Generalizations of Riemannian manifolds include pseudo-Riemannian manifolds, Finsler manifolds, and sub-Riemannian manifolds.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] In 1827, Carl Friedrich Gauss discovered that the Gaussian curvature of a surface embedded in 3-dimensional space only depends on local measurements made within the surface (the first fundamental form).
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] This result is known as the Theorema Egregium ("remarkable theorem" in Latin).
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] A map that preserves the local measurements of a surface is called a local isometry.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] A property of a surface is called an intrinsic property if it is preserved by local isometries and it is called an extrinsic property if it is not.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] In this language, the Theorema Egregium says that the Gaussian curvature is an intrinsic property of surfaces.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Riemannian manifolds and their curvature were first introduced non-rigorously by Bernhard Riemann in 1854.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] However, they would not be formalized until much later.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] In fact, the more primitive concept of a smooth manifold was first explicitly defined only in 1913 in a book by Hermann Weyl.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Élie Cartan introduced the Cartan connection, one of the first concepts of a connection.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Levi-Civita defined the Levi-Civita connection, a special connection on a Riemannian manifold.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Albert Einstein used the theory of pseudo-Riemannian manifolds (a generalization of Riemannian manifolds) to develop general relativity.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Specifically, the Einstein field equations are constraints on the curvature of spacetime, which is a 4-dimensional pseudo-Riemannian manifold.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] For each point $p\in M$ , there is an associated vector space $T_{p}M$ called the tangent space of M at p .
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Vectors in $T_{p}M$ are thought of as the vectors tangent to M at p .
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] However, $T_{p}M$ does not come equipped with an inner product, a "measuring stick" that gives tangent vectors a concept of length and angle.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] This is an important deficiency because calculus teaches that to calculate the length of a curve, the length of vectors tangent to the curve must be defined.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] A Riemannian metric puts such a "measuring stick" on every tangent space.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] A *Riemannian metric* g on M assigns to each p a positive-definite symmetric bilinear form (i.e. an inner product) $g_{p}:T_{p}M\times T_{p}M\to \mathbb {R}$ in a smooth way (see the section on regularity below).
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] A smooth manifold M endowed with a Riemannian metric g is a *Riemannian manifold*, denoted $(M,g)$ .
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] A Riemannian metric is a special case of a metric tensor.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] A Riemannian metric is not to be confused with the distance function of a metric space, which is also called a metric.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] form a basis of the vector space $T_{p}M$ for any $p\in U$ .
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] These $n^{2}$ functions $g_{ij}:U\to \mathbb {R}$ can be put together into an $n\times n$ matrix-valued function on U .
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] The requirement that $g_{p}$ is a positive-definite inner product then says exactly that this matrix-valued function is a symmetric positive-definite matrix at p .
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] The Riemannian metric g is *continuous* if its components $g_{ij}:U\to \mathbb {R}$ are continuous in any smooth coordinate chart $(U,x).$ The Riemannian metric g is *smooth* if its components $g_{ij}$ are smooth in any smooth coordinate chart.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] One can consider many other types of Riemannian metrics in this spirit, such as Lipschitz Riemannian metrics or measurable Riemannian metrics.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] There are situations in geometric analysis in which one wants to consider non-smooth Riemannian metrics.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] See for instance (Gromov 1999) and (Shi and Tam 2002).
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] However, in this article, g is assumed to be smooth unless stated otherwise.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] In analogy to how an inner product on a vector space induces an isomorphism between a vector space and its dual given by $v\mapsto \langle v,\cdot \rangle$ , a Riemannian metric induces an isomorphism of bundles between the tangent bundle and the cotangent bundle.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] is a isomorphism of smooth vector bundles from the tangent bundle $TM$ to the cotangent bundle $T^{*}M$ .
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] An isometry is a function between Riemannian manifolds which preserves all of the structure of Riemannian manifolds.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] If two Riemannian manifolds have an isometry between them, they are called *isometric*, and they are considered to be the same manifold for the purpose of Riemannian geometry.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] for all $p\in M$ and $u,v\in T_{p}M.$ For example, translations and rotations are both isometries from Euclidean space (to be defined soon) to itself.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] One says that a smooth map $f:M\to N,$ not assumed to be a diffeomorphism, is a *local isometry* if every $p\in M$ has an open neighborhood U such that $f:U\to f(U)$ is an isometry (and thus a diffeomorphism).
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] An oriented n -dimensional Riemannian manifold $(M,g)$ has a unique n -form $dV_{g}$ called the *Riemannian volume form*.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] The Riemannian volume form is preserved by orientation-preserving isometries.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] The volume form gives rise to a measure on M which allows measurable functions to be integrated.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] If M is compact, the *volume of M* is $\int _{M}dV_{g}$ .
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] The Riemannian manifold $(\mathbb {R} ^{n},g^{\text{can}})$ is called *Euclidean space*.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Let $(M,g)$ be a Riemannian manifold and let $i:N\to M$ be an immersed submanifold or an embedded submanifold of M .
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] The pullback $i^{*}g$ of g is a Riemannian metric on N , and $(N,i^{*}g)$ is said to be a *Riemannian submanifold* of $(M,g)$ .
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] In the case where $N\subseteq M$ , the map $i:N\to M$ is given by $i(x)=x$ and the metric $i^{*}g$ is just the restriction of g to vectors tangent along N .
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] On the other hand, if N already has a Riemannian metric ${\tilde {g}}$ , then the immersion (or embedding) $i:N\to M$ is called an *isometric immersion* (or *isometric embedding*) if ${\tilde {g}}=i^{*}g$ .
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Hence isometric immersions and isometric embeddings are Riemannian submanifolds.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] naturally carries a Euclidean metric, obtained by identifying opposite sides of a square (left).
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] , cannot be isometrically embedded in 3-dimensional Euclidean space (right), because it is necessary to bend and stretch the sheet in doing so.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Thus the intrinsic geometry of a flat torus is different from that of an embedded torus.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Let $(M,g)$ and $(N,h)$ be two Riemannian manifolds, and consider the product manifold $M\times N$ .
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] The Riemannian metrics g and h naturally put a Riemannian metric ${\widetilde {g}}$ on $M\times N,$ which can be described in a few ways.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] For example, consider the n -torus $T^{n}=S^{1}\times \cdots \times S^{1}$ .
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] If each copy of $S^{1}$ is given the round metric, the product Riemannian manifold $T^{n}$ is called the *flat torus*.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] As another example, the Riemannian product $\mathbb {R} \times \cdots \times \mathbb {R}$ , where each copy of $\mathbb {R}$ has the Euclidean metric, is isometric to $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ with the Euclidean metric.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Although much of the basic theory of Riemannian metrics can be developed using only that a smooth manifold is a locally Euclidean topological space, for this result it is necessary to use that smooth manifolds are Hausdorff and paracompact.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] The reason is that the proof makes use of a partition of unity.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] An alternative proof uses the Whitney embedding theorem to embed M into Euclidean space and then pulls back the metric from Euclidean space to M .
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Therefore, one could argue that nothing can be gained from the consideration of abstract smooth manifolds and their Riemannian metrics.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] An *admissible curve* is a piecewise smooth curve $\gamma :[0,1]\to M$ whose velocity $\gamma '(t)\in T_{\gamma (t)}M$ is nonzero everywhere it is defined.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] The nonnegative function $t\mapsto \|\gamma '(t)\|_{\gamma (t)}$ is defined on the interval $[0,1]$ except for at finitely many points.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] The integrand is bounded and continuous except at finitely many points, so it is integrable.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Although the length of a curve is given by an explicit formula, it is generally impossible to write out the distance function $d_{g}$ by any explicit means.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] In fact, if M is compact, there always exist points where $d_{g}:M\times M\to \mathbb {R}$ is non-differentiable, and it can be remarkably difficult to even determine the location or nature of these points, even in seemingly simple cases such as when $(M,g)$ is an ellipsoid.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] The Hopf–Rinow theorem shows that if $(M,d_{g})$ is complete and has finite diameter, it is compact.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Conversely, if $(M,d_{g})$ is compact, then the function $d_{g}:M\times M\to \mathbb {R}$ has a maximum, since it is a continuous function on a compact metric space.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] This is not the case without the completeness assumption; for counterexamples one could consider any open bounded subset of a Euclidean space with the standard Riemannian metric.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] It is also not true that *any* complete metric space of finite diameter must be compact; it matters that the metric space came from a Riemannian manifold.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] An (affine) connection is an additional structure on a Riemannian manifold that defines differentiation of one vector field with respect to another.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Connections contain geometric data, and two Riemannian manifolds with different connections have different geometry.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Let ${\mathfrak {X}}(M)$ denote the space of vector fields on M .
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] The product rule $\nabla _{X}fY=X(f)Y+f\,\nabla _{X}Y$ holds.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] The expression $\nabla _{X}Y$ is called the *covariant derivative of Y with respect to X*.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Two Riemannian manifolds with different connections have different geometry.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Thankfully, there is a natural connection associated to a Riemannian manifold called the Levi-Civita connection.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] where $[\cdot ,\cdot ]$ is the Lie bracket.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] A *Levi-Civita connection* is a torsion-free connection that preserves the metric.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Once a Riemannian metric is fixed, there exists a unique Levi-Civita connection.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Note that the definition of preserving the metric uses the regularity of g .
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] If $\gamma :[0,1]\to M$ is a smooth curve, a *smooth vector field along $\gamma$* is a smooth map $X:[0,1]\to TM$ such that $X(t)\in T_{\gamma (t)}M$ for all $t\in [0,1]$ .
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] The set ${\mathfrak {X}}(\gamma )$ of smooth vector fields along $\gamma$ is a vector space under pointwise vector addition and scalar multiplication.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Let X be a smooth vector field along $\gamma$ .
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] If ${\tilde {X}}$ is a smooth vector field on a neighborhood of the image of $\gamma$ such that $X(t)={\tilde {X}}_{\gamma (t)}$ , then ${\tilde {X}}$ is called an *extension of X*.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] (left), the maximal geodesics are straight lines.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Geodesics are curves with no intrinsic acceleration.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Equivalently, geodesics are curves that locally take the shortest path between two points.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] They are the generalization of straight lines in Euclidean space to arbitrary Riemannian manifolds.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] An ant living in a Riemannian manifold walking straight ahead without making any effort to accelerate or turn would trace out a geodesic.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Let $\gamma :[0,1]\to M$ be a smooth curve.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] The *acceleration of $\gamma$* is the vector field $D_{t}\gamma '$ along $\gamma$ .
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] If $D_{t}\gamma '=0$ for all t , $\gamma$ is called a *geodesic*.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] For every $p\in M$ and $v\in T_{p}M$ , there exists a geodesic $\gamma :I\to M$ defined on some open interval I containing 0 such that $\gamma (0)=p$ and $\gamma '(0)=v$ .
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Any two such geodesics agree on their common domain.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Taking the union over all open intervals I containing 0 on which a geodesic satisfying $\gamma (0)=p$ and $\gamma '(0)=v$ exists, one obtains a geodesic called a *maximal geodesic* of which every geodesic satisfying $\gamma (0)=p$ and $\gamma '(0)=v$ is a restriction.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Every curve $\gamma :[0,1]\to M$ that has the shortest length of any admissible curve with the same endpoints as $\gamma$ is a geodesic (in a unit-speed reparameterization).
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] The Riemannian manifold M with its Levi-Civita connection is *geodesically complete* if the domain of every maximal geodesic is $(-\infty ,\infty )$ .
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] The plane $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ is geodesically complete.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] On the other hand, the punctured plane $\mathbb {R} ^{2}\smallsetminus \{(0,0)\}$ with the restriction of the Riemannian metric from $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ is not geodesically complete as the maximal geodesic with initial conditions $p=(1,1)$ , $v=(1,1)$ does not have domain $\mathbb {R}$ .
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] The Hopf–Rinow theorem characterizes geodesically complete manifolds.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] In Euclidean space, all tangent spaces are canonically identified with each other via translation, so it is easy to move vectors from one tangent space to another.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Parallel transport is a way of moving vectors from one tangent space to another along a curve in the setting of a general Riemannian manifold.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Given a fixed connection, there is a unique way to do parallel transport.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Specifically, call a smooth vector field V along a smooth curve $\gamma$ *parallel along $\gamma$* if $D_{t}V=0$ identically.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Fix a curve $\gamma :[0,1]\to M$ with $\gamma (0)=p$ and $\gamma (1)=q$ . to parallel transport a vector $v\in T_{p}M$ to a vector in $T_{q}M$ along $\gamma$ , first extend v to a vector field parallel along $\gamma$ , and then take the value of this vector field at q .
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] The images below show parallel transport induced by the Levi-Civita connection associated to two different Riemannian metrics on the punctured plane $\mathbb {R} ^{2}\smallsetminus \{0,0\}$ .
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] The curve the parallel transport is done along is the unit circle.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] In polar coordinates, the metric on the left is the standard Euclidean metric $dx^{2}+dy^{2}=dr^{2}+r^{2}\,d\theta ^{2}$ , while the metric on the right is $dr^{2}+d\theta ^{2}$ .
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] This second metric has a singularity at the origin, so it does not extend past the puncture, but the first metric extends to the entire plane.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Warning: This is parallel transport on the punctured plane *along* the unit circle, not parallel transport *on* the unit circle.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Indeed, in the first image, the vectors fall outside of the tangent space to the unit circle.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] The Riemann curvature tensor measures precisely the extent to which parallel transporting vectors around a small rectangle is not the identity map.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] The Riemann curvature tensor is 0 at every point if and only if the manifold is locally isometric to Euclidean space.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] where $[X,Y]$ is the Lie bracket of vector fields.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] The Riemann curvature tensor is a $(1,3)$ -tensor field.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] where $\operatorname {tr}$ is the trace.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] The Ricci curvature tensor is a covariant 2-tensor field.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] The Ricci curvature tensor $Ric$ plays a defining role in the theory of Einstein manifolds, which has applications to the study of gravity.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] holds, and a (pseudo-)Riemannian manifold whose metric is Einstein is called an *Einstein manifold*.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Examples of Einstein manifolds include Euclidean space, the n -sphere, hyperbolic space, and complex projective space with the Fubini-Study metric.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] A Riemannian manifold is said to have *constant curvature* κ if every sectional curvature equals the number κ.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] This implies that the Ricci curvature is given by *R**jk* = (*n* − 1)*κg**jk* and the scalar curvature is *n*(*n* − 1)*κ*, where n is the dimension of the manifold.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] In particular, every Riemannian manifold of constant curvature is an Einstein manifold, thereby having constant scalar curvature.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Any two Riemannian manifolds of the same constant curvature are locally isometric, and so it follows that any Riemannian manifold of constant curvature κ can be covered by coordinate charts relative to which the metric has the above form.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] A *Riemannian space form* is a Riemannian manifold with constant curvature which is additionally connected and geodesically complete.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] A Riemannian space form is said to be a *spherical space form* if the curvature is positive, a *Euclidean space form* if the curvature is zero, and a *hyperbolic space form* or *hyperbolic manifold* if the curvature is negative.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] In any dimension, the sphere with its standard Riemannian metric, Euclidean space, and hyperbolic space are Riemannian space forms of constant curvature 1, 0, and −1 respectively.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Furthermore, the Killing–Hopf theorem says that any simply connected spherical space form is homothetic to the sphere, any simply connected Euclidean space form is homothetic to Euclidean space, and any simply connected hyperbolic space form is homothetic to hyperbolic space.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Using the covering manifold construction, any Riemannian space form is isometric to the quotient manifold of a simply connected Riemannian space form, modulo a certain group action of isometries.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] For example, the isometry group of the n-sphere is the orthogonal group O(*n* + 1).
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Up to homothety, every spherical space form arises in this way; this largely reduces the study of spherical space forms to problems in group theory.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] For instance, this can be used to show directly that every even-dimensional spherical space form is homothetic to the standard metric on either the sphere or real projective space.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] There are many more odd-dimensional spherical space forms, although there are known algorithms for their classification.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] The list of three-dimensional spherical space forms is infinite but explicitly known, and includes the lens spaces and the Poincaré dodecahedral space.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] The case of Euclidean and hyperbolic space forms can likewise be reduced to group theory, based on study of the isometry group of Euclidean space and hyperbolic space.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] For example, the class of two-dimensional Euclidean space forms includes Riemannian metrics on the Klein bottle, the Möbius strip, the torus, the cylinder *S*1 × ℝ, along with the Euclidean plane.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Unlike the case of two-dimensional spherical space forms, in some cases two space form structures on the same manifold are not homothetic.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] The case of two-dimensional hyperbolic space forms is even more complicated, having to do with Teichmüller space.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] In three dimensions, the Euclidean space forms are known, while the geometry of hyperbolic space forms in three and higher dimensions remains an area of active research known as hyperbolic geometry.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Let G be a Lie group, such as the group of rotations in three-dimensional space.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Using the group structure, any inner product on the tangent space at the identity (or any other particular tangent space) can be transported to all other tangent spaces to define a Riemannian metric.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] where for arbitrary x, *L**x* is the left multiplication map *G* → *G* sending a point y to *xy*.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Riemannian metrics constructed this way are *left-invariant*; right-invariant Riemannian metrics could be constructed likewise using the right multiplication map instead.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] The Levi-Civita connection and curvature of a general left-invariant Riemannian metric can be computed explicitly in terms of *g**e*, the adjoint representation of G, and the Lie algebra associated to G.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] These formulas simplify considerably in the special case of a Riemannian metric which is *bi-invariant* (that is, simultaneously left- and right-invariant).
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] All left-invariant metrics have constant scalar curvature.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Left- and bi-invariant metrics on Lie groups are an important source of examples of Riemannian manifolds.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Berger spheres, constructed as left-invariant metrics on the special unitary group SU(2), are among the simplest examples of the collapsing phenomena, in which a simply connected Riemannian manifold can have small volume without having large curvature.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] They also give an example of a Riemannian metric which has constant scalar curvature but which is not Einstein, or even of parallel Ricci curvature.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Hyperbolic space can be given a Lie group structure relative to which the metric is left-invariant.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Any bi-invariant Riemannian metric on a Lie group has nonnegative sectional curvature, giving a variety of such metrics: a Lie group can be given a bi-invariant Riemannian metric if and only if it is the product of a compact Lie group with an abelian Lie group.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] A Riemannian manifold (*M*, *g*) is said to be *homogeneous* if for every pair of points x and y in M, there is some isometry f of the Riemannian manifold sending x to y.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] This can be rephrased in the language of group actions as the requirement that the natural action of the isometry group is transitive.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Every homogeneous Riemannian manifold is geodesically complete and has constant scalar curvature.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Up to isometry, all homogeneous Riemannian manifolds arise by the following construction.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Given a Lie group G with compact subgroup K which does not contain any nontrivial normal subgroup of G, fix any complemented subspace W of the Lie algebra of K within the Lie algebra of G.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] If this subspace is invariant under the linear map ad*G*(*k*): *W* → *W* for any element k of K, then G-invariant Riemannian metrics on the coset space *G*/*K* are in one-to-one correspondence with those inner products on W which are invariant under ad*G*(*k*): *W* → *W* for every element k of K.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Each such Riemannian metric is homogeneous, with G naturally viewed as a subgroup of the full isometry group.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] The above example of Lie groups with left-invariant Riemannian metrics arises as a very special case of this construction, namely when K is the trivial subgroup containing only the identity element.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] This reduces the study of the curvature of homogeneous Riemannian manifolds largely to algebraic problems.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] This reduction, together with the flexibility of the above construction, makes the class of homogeneous Riemannian manifolds very useful for constructing examples.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] A connected Riemannian manifold (*M*, *g*) is said to be *symmetric* if for every point p of M there exists some isometry of the manifold with p as a fixed point and for which the negation of the differential at p is the identity map.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Every Riemannian symmetric space is homogeneous, and consequently is geodesically complete and has constant scalar curvature.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] However, Riemannian symmetric spaces also have a much stronger curvature property not possessed by most homogeneous Riemannian manifolds, namely that the Riemann curvature tensor and Ricci curvature are parallel.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Riemannian manifolds with this curvature property, which could loosely be phrased as "constant Riemann curvature tensor" (not to be confused with constant curvature), are said to be *locally symmetric*.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] This property nearly characterizes symmetric spaces; Élie Cartan proved in the 1920s that a locally symmetric Riemannian manifold which is geodesically complete and simply-connected must in fact be symmetric.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Many of the fundamental examples of Riemannian manifolds are symmetric.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] The most basic include the sphere and real projective spaces with their standard metrics, along with hyperbolic space.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] The complex projective space, quaternionic projective space, and Cayley plane are analogues of the real projective space which are also symmetric, as are complex hyperbolic space, quaternionic hyperbolic space, and Cayley hyperbolic space, which are instead analogues of hyperbolic space.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Grassmannian manifolds also carry natural Riemannian metrics making them into symmetric spaces.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Among the Lie groups with left-invariant Riemannian metrics, those which are bi-invariant are symmetric.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Based on their algebraic formulation as special kinds of homogeneous spaces, Cartan achieved an explicit classification of symmetric spaces which are *irreducible*, referring to those which cannot be locally decomposed as product spaces.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Every such space is an example of an Einstein manifold; among them only the one-dimensional manifolds have zero scalar curvature.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] These spaces are important from the perspective of Riemannian holonomy.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] As found in the 1950s by Marcel Berger, any Riemannian manifold which is simply connected and irreducible is either a symmetric space or has Riemannian holonomy belonging to a list of only seven possibilities.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Six of the seven exceptions to symmetric spaces in Berger's classification fall into the fields of Kähler geometry, quaternion-Kähler geometry, G2 geometry, and Spin(7) geometry, each of which study Riemannian manifolds equipped with certain extra structures and symmetries.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] The seventh exception is the study of 'generic' Riemannian manifolds with no particular symmetry, as reflected by the maximal possible holonomy group.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Riemannian metrics are defined in a way similar to the finite-dimensional case.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Length of curves and the Riemannian distance function $d_{g}:M\times M\to [0,\infty )$ are defined in a way similar to the finite-dimensional case.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] The distance function $d_{g}$ , called the *geodesic distance*, is always a pseudometric (a metric that does not separate points), but it may not be a metric.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] In the finite-dimensional case, the proof that the Riemannian distance function separates points uses the existence of a pre-compact open set around any point.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] In the infinite case, open sets are no longer pre-compact, so the proof fails.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] In the case of strong Riemannian metrics, one part of the finite-dimensional Hopf–Rinow still holds.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] However, a geodesically complete strong Riemannian manifold might not be metrically complete and it might have closed and bounded subsets that are not compact.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] Further, a strong Riemannian manifold for which all closed and bounded subsets are compact might not be geodesically complete.
[src:differential-geometry/riemannian-manifold] If g is a weak Riemannian metric, then no notion of completeness implies the other in general.
[src:differential-geometry/tangent-space] In mathematics, the **tangent space** of a manifold is a generalization of *tangent lines* to curves in two-dimensional space and *tangent planes* to surfaces in three-dimensional space in higher dimensions.
[src:differential-geometry/tangent-space] In the context of physics, the tangent space to a manifold at a point can be viewed as the space of possible velocities for a particle moving on the manifold.
[src:differential-geometry/tangent-space] In differential geometry, one can attach to every point x of a differentiable manifold a *tangent space*—a real vector space that intuitively contains the possible directions in which one can tangentially pass through x .
[src:differential-geometry/tangent-space] The elements of the tangent space at x are called the *tangent vectors* at x .
[src:differential-geometry/tangent-space] This is a generalization of the notion of a vector, based at a given initial point, in a Euclidean space.
[src:differential-geometry/tangent-space] The dimension of the tangent space at every point of a connected manifold is the same as that of the manifold itself.
